# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vehicle-to-grid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] BEVs include – but are not limited to – all battery-driven electric cars, buses, trucks, forklifts, motorcycles and scooters, bicycles, skateboards, railcars, boat and personal watercraft, although in common usage the term usually refers specifically to passenger cars.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In 2016, there were 210 million electric bikes worldwide used daily.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Cumulative global sales of highway-capable light-duty pure electric car vehicles passed the one million unit milestone in September 2016.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] As of September 2024, the world's top-selling all-electric car in history is the Tesla Model Y, with an estimated 3.4 million sales, followed by the Tesla Model 3 with over 2.6 million sales, and the Wuling Hongguang Mini EV with 1.4 million sales as of May 2024.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] During the 1880s, Gustave Trouvé, Thomas Parker and Andreas Flocken built experimental electric cars, but the first practical battery electric vehicles appeared during the 1890s.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Battery vehicle milk floats expanded in 1931, and by 1968, gave Britain the largest electric vehicle fleet in the world.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Hybrid electric vehicles use both electric motors and internal combustion engines, and are not considered pure or all-electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Hybrid electric vehicles whose batteries can be charged externally are called plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEV) and run as BEVs during their charge-depleting mode.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] PHEVs with a series powertrain are also called range-extended electric vehicles (REEVs), such as the Chevrolet Volt and Fisker Karma.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Plug-in electric vehicles (PEVs) are a subcategory of electric vehicles that includes battery electric vehicles (BEVs) and plug-in hybrid vehicles (PHEVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The electric vehicle conversions of hybrid electric vehicles and conventional internal combustion engine vehicles (aka all-combustion vehicles) belong to one of the two categories.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In China, plug-in electric vehicles, together with hybrid electric vehicles are called new energy vehicles (NEVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The concept of battery electric vehicles is to use charged batteries on board vehicles for propulsion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Battery electric cars are becoming more and more attractive with the higher oil prices and the advancement of new battery technology (lithium-ion) that have higher power and energy density (i.e., greater possible acceleration and more range with fewer batteries).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Compared to older battery types such as lead-acid batteries, lithium-ion batteries for example now have an energy density of 0.9–2.63 MJ/L whereas lead-acid batteries had an energy density of 0.36 MJ/L (so 2.5 to 7.3x higher).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] There is still a long way to go if comparing it to petroleum-based fuels and biofuels, however (gasoline having an energy density of 34.2 MJ/L -38x to 12.92x higher- and ethanol having an energy of 24 MJ/L -26x to 9.12x higher-).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This is partially offset by higher conversion efficiency of electric motors – BEVs travel roughly 3x further than similar-size internal combustion vehicles per MJ of stored energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] BEVs include automobiles, light trucks, and neighborhood electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Battery electric trains in the form of BEMUs (battery electric multiple units) are operated commercially in Japan.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] They are charged via pantographs, either when driving on electrified railway lines or during stops at specially equipped train stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] They use battery power for propulsion when driving on railway lines that are not electrified, and have successfully replaced diesel multiple units on some such lines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Other countries have also tested or ordered such vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Battery electric trams eliminate the need for overhead wires, which can be beneficial in historic city centers or where overhead wires are not desirable otherwise.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Due to the frequent stops of trams, the batteries can be charged at every stop, where energy is rapidly stored in a combination of supercapacitors and batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Chattanooga, Tennessee, operates nine zero-fare electric buses, which have been in operation since 1992 and have carried 11.3 million passengers and covered a distance of 3,100,000 kilometres (1,900,000 mi).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] They were made locally by Advanced Vehicle Systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Two of these buses were used for the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Beginning in the summer of 2000, Hong Kong Airport began operating a 16-passenger Mitsubishi Rosa electric shuttle bus, and in the fall of 2000, New York City began testing a 66-passenger battery-powered school bus, an all-electric version of the Blue Bird TC/2000.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] A similar bus was operated in Napa Valley, California, for 14 months ending in April 2004.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The 2008 Beijing Olympics used a fleet of 50 electric buses, which have a range of 130 km (81 mi) with the air conditioning on.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] They use lithium-ion batteries, and consume about 1 kW⋅h/mi (0.62 kW⋅h/km; 2.2 MJ/km).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The buses were designed by the Beijing Institute of Technology and built by the Jinghua Coach.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The batteries are replaced with fully charged ones at the recharging station to allow 24-hour operation of the buses.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In France, the electric bus phenomenon is in development, but some buses are already operating in numerous cities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] PVI, a medium-sized company located in the Paris region, is one of the leaders of the market with its brand Gepebus (offering Oreos 2X and Oreos 4X).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In the United States, the first battery-electric, fast-charge bus has been in operation in Pomona, California, since September 2010 at Foothill Transit.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The Proterra EcoRide BE35 uses lithium-titanate batteries and is able to fast-charge in less than 10 minutes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In 2012, heavy-duty trucks and buses contributed 7% of global warming emissions in California.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In 2014, the first production model all-electric school bus was delivered to the Kings Canyon Unified School District in California's San Joaquin Valley.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The bus was one of four the district ordered.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This battery-electric school bus, which has four sodium nickel batteries, is the first modern electric school bus approved for student transportation by any state.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In 2016, including the light heavy-duty vehicles, there were roughly 1.5 million heavy-duty vehicles in California.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The same technology is used to power the Mountain View Community Shuttles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This technology was supported by the California Energy Commission, and the shuttle program is being supported by Google.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The buses will also be built in the United States and Finland.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Tindo is an all-electric bus from Adelaide, Australia.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The Tindo (aboriginal word for sun) is made by Designline International in New Zealand and gets its electricity from a solar PV system on Adelaide's central bus station.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Rides are zero-fare as part of Adelaide's public transport system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Proterra's EcoRide BE35 transit bus, called the Ecoliner by Foothill Transit in West Covina, California, is a heavy-duty, fast charge, battery-electric bus.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Proterra's ProDrive drive-system uses a UQM motor and regenerative braking that captures 90 percent of the available energy and returns it to the TerraVolt energy storage system, which in turn increases the total distance the bus can drive by 31–35 percent.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] It can travel 30–40 miles (48–64 km) on a single charge, is up to 600 percent more fuel-efficient than a typical diesel or CNG bus, and produces 44 percent less carbon than CNG.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Proterra buses have had several problems, most notably in Philadelphia where the entire fleet was removed from service.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] For most of the 20th century, the majority of the world's battery electric road vehicles were British milk floats.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The 21st century saw the massive development of BYD electric trucks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In March 2012, Smith Electric Vehicles announced the release of the Newton Step-Van, an all-electric, zero-emission vehicle built on the versatile Newton platform that features a walk-in body produced by Indiana-based Utilimaster.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Due to a lack of BEV van offerings by legacy auto makers, in December 2014, Deutsche Post DHL purchased the Aachen-based StreetScooter company, to produce battery electric mail delivery vans according to their needs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In addition, BYD supplies DHL with electric distribution fleet of commercial BYD T3.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Recharging can also take significant lengths of time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] For journeys within a single battery charge, rather than long journeys, electric cars are practical forms of transportation and can be recharged overnight.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Electric cars can significantly reduce city pollution by having zero emissions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Vehicle greenhouse gas savings depend on how the electricity is generated.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Electric cars are having a major impact in the auto industry given advantages in city pollution, less dependence on oil and combustion, and scarcity and expected rise in gasoline prices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] World governments are pledging billions to fund development of electric vehicles and their components.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Formula E is a fully electric international single-seater championship.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The series was conceived in 2012, and the inaugural championship started in Beijing on 13 September 2014.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Alejandro Agag is the current CEO of Formula E.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The Formula E championship is currently contested by ten teams with two drivers each (after the withdrawal of Team Trulli, there are temporarily only nine teams competing).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Racing generally takes place on temporary city-center street circuits which are approximately 2 to 3.4 kilometres (1.2 to 2.1 mi) long.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Currently, only the Mexico City ePrix takes place on a road course, a modified version of the Autódromo Hermanos Rodríguez.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Special-purpose vehicles come in a wide range of types, ranging from relatively common ones such as golf carts, things like electric golf trolleys, milk floats, all-terrain vehicles, neighborhood electric vehicles, and a wide range of other devices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Certain manufacturers specialize in electric-powered "in plant" work machines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Three-wheeled vehicles include electric rickshaws, a powered variant of the cycle rickshaw.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The large-scale adoption of electric two-wheelers can reduce traffic noise and road congestion but may necessitate adaptations of the existing urban infrastructure and safety regulations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Ather Energy from India has launched their BLDC motor powered Ather 450 electric scooter with Lithium Ion batteries in 2018.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Also from India, AVERA – a new and renewable energy company is going to launch two models of electric scooters at the end of 2010, with Lithium Iron Phosphate Battery technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In 2024, electric two-wheelers was a $1.3 million market in India.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] China is the world's largest market for electric 2 wheelers, with electric models totalling $6.9 million in 2024.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The 2 wheeler market is moving towards higher value motorcyle models.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] As a result, Chinese governments launched a trade in programme for electric bicycles in 2024 to boost sales of 2/3 wheeler electric vehicles. however, there are areas where 2 wheelers are banned, so electric bicycles are popular amongst commuters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] India is the world's biggest market for bicycles at 22 million units per year.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The Indian government is launching schemes and incentives to promote the adoption of electric vehicles in the country, and is aiming to be a manufacturing hub for electric vehicles within the next five years.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] China has experienced an explosive growth of sales of non-assisted e-bikes including the scooter type, with annual sales jumping from 56,000 units in 1998 to over 21 million in 2008, and reaching an estimated 120 million e-bikes on the road in early 2010.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] An increasing variety of personal transporters are being manufactured, including the one-wheeled self-balancing unicycles, self-balancing scooters, electric kick scooters, and electric skateboards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Several battery electric ships operate throughout the world, some for business.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Electric ferries are being operated and constructed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The motor controller receives a signal from potentiometers linked to the accelerator pedal, and it uses this signal to determine how much electric power is needed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This DC power is supplied by the battery pack, and the controller regulates the power to the motor, supplying either variable pulse width DC or variable frequency variable amplitude AC, depending on the motor type.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The controller also handles regenerative braking, whereby electrical power is gathered as the vehicle slows down and this power recharges the battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In addition to power and motor management, the controller performs various safety checks such as anomaly detection, functional safety tests and failure diagnostics.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Most electric vehicles today use an electric battery, consisting of electrochemical cells with external connections in order to provide power to the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Battery technology for EVs has developed from early lead-acid batteries used in the late 19th century to the 2010s, to lithium-ion batteries which are found in most EVs today.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The overall battery is referred to as a battery pack, which is a group of multiple battery modules and cells.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] For example, the Tesla Model S battery pack has up to 7,104 cells, split into 16 modules with 6 groups of 74 cells in each.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Each cell has a nominal voltage of 3–4 volts, depending on its chemical composition.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Electric cars have traditionally used series wound DC motors, a form of brushed DC electric motor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Separately excited and permanent magnet are just two of the types of DC motors available.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] More recent electric vehicles have made use of a variety of AC motor types, as these are simpler to build and have no brushes that can wear out.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] These are usually induction motors or brushless AC electric motors which use permanent magnets.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] There are several variations of the permanent magnet motor which offer simpler drive schemes and/or lower cost including the brushless DC electric motor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Once electric power is supplied to the motor (from the controller), the magnetic field interaction inside the motor will turn the drive shaft and ultimately the vehicle's wheels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] EV battery storage is a key element for the global energy transition which is dependent on more electricity storage right now.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] As energy availability is the most important factor for the vitality of an economy the mobile storage infrastructure of EV batteries can be seen as one of the most meaningful infrastructure projects facilitating the energy transition to a fully sustainable economy based on renewables.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] A meta-study graphically showing the importance of electricity storage depicts the technology in context.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Electric vehicles produce no greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in operation, but the electricity used to power them may do so in its generation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The two factors driving the emissions of battery electric vehicles are the carbon intensity of the electricity used to recharge the Electric Vehicle (commonly expressed in grams of CO2 per kWh) and the consumption of the specific vehicle (in kilometers/kWh).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The carbon intensity of electricity varies depending on the source of electricity where it is consumed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] A country with a high share of renewable energy in its electricity mix will have a low C.I.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In the European Union, in 2013, the carbon intensity had a strong geographic variability but in most of the member states, electric vehicles were "greener" than conventional ones.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] On average, electric cars saved 50–60% of CO2 emissions compared to diesel and gasoline fuelled engines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Moreover, the de-carbonisation process is constantly reducing the GHG emissions due to the use of electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In the European Union, on average, between 2009 and 2013 there was a reduction in the electricity carbon intensity of 17%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In a life-cycle assessment perspective, considering the GHG necessary to build the battery and its end-of-life, the GHG savings are 10–13% lower.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The open source VencoPy model framework can be used to study the interactions between vehicles, owners, and the electricity system at large.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] GHGs are also emitted when the electric vehicle is being manufactured.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The lithium-ion batteries used in the vehicle take more materials and energy to produce because of the extraction process of the lithium and cobalt essential to the battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This means the bigger the electric vehicle, the more carbon dioxide emitted.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The same size-to-emission relationship applies to manufacturing of all products.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Along with terrestrial mining, deep sea mining is a means by which vital minerals such as nickel, copper, cobalt, manganese, zinc, gold and rare-earth metals can be procured.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] As the name suggests, large robotic cutting machines are used to strip away large areas of the ocean floor in search of minerals embedded within it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] These minerals appear as mineral formations such as polymetallic nodules that are roughly the size of a potato.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Currently, sea mining projects are underway in areas such as the Clarion-Clipperton Zone (CCZ) in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] While there is an abundance of minerals to be found in the ocean, there are many concerns in regards to the environmental impact of deep sea mining.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Marine habitats and ecosystems are not only widely understudied, they are also extremely temperamental and even slight disturbances can be incredibly destructive.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Deep sea mining affects the quality of the water through sediment plumes and the release of carbon dioxide trapped within ocean floors, directly endangering marine life in the area.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Sound pollution is also harmful to marine life in many mining sites, such as dolphins and whales.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Current research suggests that BEVs (battery electric vehicles) are the most efficient in reducing GHGs (greenhouse gases).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] These include: the cost of this type of vehicle, the availability of charging stations, their range versus that of an internal combustion engine, and the cost of repairs/replacement parts.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Other factors affecting the adoption of BEV technology are more nuanced or political.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In the United States, political ideology impacts the adoption of BEVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Those who identify as Republican are less likely to purchase BEVs than those who identify as Democrats.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This phenomenon likely has its roots in the positions of the parties regarding environmentalism and climate change.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Historically, Republicans have expressed negative attitudes towards environmental and climate change policies; conversely, Democrats tend to be in favor of these types of policies A current example of this polarity can be found within both party's 2024 platforms.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Another important occurrence in recent years is the rise of right-wing populism within the Republican party under the leadership of Donald Trump.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Trump and those within his party known as "MAGA-Republicans" have espoused greater skepticism of the effects of climate change and policies that aim to regulate industries such as that of fossil fuel.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] However, there are Republicans and other conservatives that are working towards changing these attitudes within party lines, which may allow for bipartisan cooperation in adopting cleaner energy technologies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] In Japan, where EV technology started developing after World War II, there is domestic resistance to the diffusion of this technology that results from both the general public's wariness and the unique composition of the automotive industry in this country.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Concerns from Japanese citizens are similar to those of the global public (i.e. infrastructure, price, grid capacity, performance, etc.) For automotive manufacturers, however, the diffusion of BEV technology has disruptive effects on the current infrastructure of automotive production.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Known as the KEIRETSU system, the major car companies in Japan (i.e.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Toyota, Honda, and Nissan [limitedly]) subcontract the production of specific parts to smaller, independent companies in an effort to make the overall production process more efficient.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] This system creates a top-down ("vertical"), hierarchical division of labor that includes hundreds of smaller Japanese manufacturing companies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] The more "horizontal," global cooperation-based model that EV production currently employs could be detrimental to those smaller Japanese companies employed by the major auto manufacturers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Automotive business leader, Akio Toyoda, chairman of Toyota stated recently that there are roughly 5.5 million jobs in jeopardy amidst the country's transition to EV and BEV technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/battery-electric-vehicle] Groups such as The Japanese Automobile Manufacturers Association (JAMA), who serve the interest of Japan's auto industry, have also argued that a transition to BEVs puts large amounts of jobs in the automotive industry at risk.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] There are two main types of EV chargers: alternating current (AC) charging stations and direct current (DC) charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Electric vehicle batteries can only be charged by direct current electricity, while most mains electricity is delivered from the power grid as alternating current.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] For this reason, most electric vehicles have a built-in AC-to-DC converter commonly known as the "**onboard charger**" (**OBC**).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] At an AC charging station, AC power from the grid is supplied to this onboard charger, which converts it into DC power to recharge the battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] DC chargers provide higher-power charging (which requires much larger AC-to-DC converters) by integrating the converter into the charging station, thereby avoiding size, weight, and cost constraints in vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The station then directly supplies DC power to the vehicle, bypassing the onboard converter.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Most modern electric vehicles can accept both AC and DC power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Public charging stations are typically found street-side or at retail shopping centers, government facilities, and other parking areas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Private charging stations are usually found at residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Public charging accounted for approximately 46% of global EV charging infrastructure revenue in 2025, driven by high capital investment in DC fast charging networks, grid upgrades, and highway corridor expansion projects.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations provide connectors that conform to a variety of international standards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] DC charging stations are commonly equipped with multiple connectors to charge various vehicles that use competing standards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Multiple standards have been established for charging technology to enable interoperability across vendors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Standards are available for nomenclature, power, and connectors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla developed proprietary technology in these areas and began building its charging network in 2012.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The terms "electric vehicle connector" and "electric vehicle inlet" were previously defined in the same way under Article 625 of the United States National Electrical Code (NEC) of 1999.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla, Inc. uses the term *charging station* as the location of a group of chargers, and the term *connector* for an individual EVSE.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Under the 1999 NEC, Level 1 charging equipment (as defined in the NEC handbook but not in the code) was connected to the grid through a standard NEMA 5-20R 3-prong electrical outlet with grounding, and a ground-fault circuit interrupter was required within 12 in (30 cm) of the plug.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The supply circuit required protection at 125% of the maximum rated current; for example, charging equipment rated at 16 amperes ("amps" or "A") continuous current required a breaker sized to 20 A.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Level 2 charging equipment (as defined in the handbook) was permanently wired and fastened at a fixed location under NEC-1999.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] It also required grounding and ground-fault protection; in addition, it required an interlock to prevent vehicle startup during charging and a safety breakaway for the cable and connector.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A 40 A breaker (125% of continuous maximum supply current) was required to protect the branch circuit.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] For convenience and speedier charging, many early EVs preferred that owners and operators install Level 2 charging equipment, which was connected to the EV either through an inductive paddle (Magne Charge) or a conductive connector (Avcon).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Level 3 charging equipment used an off-vehicle rectifier to convert the input AC power to DC, which was then supplied to the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] At the time it was written, the 1999 NEC handbook anticipated that Level 3 charging equipment would require utilities to upgrade their distribution systems and transformers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE International) defines the general physical, electrical, communication, and performance requirements for EV charging systems used in North America, as part of standard SAE J1772, initially developed in 2001.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] SAE J1772 defines four levels of charging, two levels each for AC and DC supplies; the differences between levels are based upon the power distribution type, standards and maximum power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] AC charging stations connect the vehicle's onboard charging circuitry directly to the AC supply.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Commonly, though incorrectly, called "Level 3" charging based on the older NEC-1999 definition, DC charging is categorized separately in the SAE standard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In DC fast-charging, grid AC power is passed through an AC-to-DC converter in the station before reaching the vehicle's battery, bypassing any AC-to-DC converter on board the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Additional standards released by SAE for charging include SAE J3068 (three-phase AC charging, using the Type 2 connector defined in IEC 62196-2) and SAE J3105 (automated connection of DC charging devices).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2003, the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) adopted a majority of the SAE J1772 standard under IEC 62196-1 for international implementation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The North American Charging Standard (NACS) was developed by Tesla, Inc. for use in the company's vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] It remained a proprietary standard until 2022 when its specifications were published by Tesla.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The connector is physically smaller than the J1772/CCS connector, and uses the same pins for both AC and DC charging functionality.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of November 2023, automakers Ford, General Motors, Rivian, Volvo, Polestar, Mercedes-Benz, Nissan, Honda, Jaguar, Fisker, Hyundai, BMW, Toyota, Subaru, and Lucid Motors have all committed to equipping their North American vehicles with NACS connectors in the future.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Automotive startup Aptera Motors has also adopted the connector standard in its vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Other automakers, such as Stellantis and Volkswagen had not made an announcement as of late 2023.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] To meet European Union (EU) requirements on recharging points, Tesla vehicles sold in the EU are equipped with a CCS Combo 2 port.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Both the North America and the EU port take 480 V DC fast charging through Tesla's network of Superchargers, which variously use NACS and CCS charging connectors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Depending on the Supercharger version, power is supplied at 72, 150, or 250 kW, the first corresponding to DC Level 1 and the second and third corresponding to DC Level 2 of SAE J1772.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of Q4 2021, Tesla reported 3,476 supercharging locations worldwide and 31,498 supercharging chargers (about 9 chargers per location on average).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] An extension to the CCS DC fast-charging standard for electric cars and light trucks was being developed as of 2020, which was slated to provide higher power charging for large commercial vehicles (Class 8, and possibly 6 and 7 as well, including school and transit buses).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] When the Charging Interface Initiative e.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] (CharIN) task force was formed in March 2018, the new standard being developed was originally called High Power Charging (HPC) for Commercial Vehicles (HPCCV), later renamed Megawatt Charging System (MCS).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] MCS is expected to operate in the range of 200–1500 V and 0–3000 A for a theoretical maximum power of 4.5 megawatts (MW).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The proposal calls for MCS charge ports to be compatible with existing CCS and HPC chargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The task force released aggregated requirements in February 2019, which called for maximum limits of 1000 V DC (optionally, 1500 V DC) and 3000 A continuous rating.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A connector design was selected in May 2019 and tested at the US National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) in September 2020.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Thirteen manufacturers participated in the test, which checked the coupling and thermal performance of seven vehicle inlets and eleven charger connectors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The final connector requirements and specification was adopted in December 2021 as MCS connector version 3.2.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] With support from Portland General Electric, on 21 April 2021 Daimler Trucks North America opened the "Electric Island", the first heavy-duty vehicle charging station, across the street from its headquarters in Portland, Oregon.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The station is capable of charging eight vehicles simultaneously, and the charging bays are sized to accommodate tractor-trailers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In addition, the design is capable of accommodating >1 MW chargers once they are available.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A startup company, WattEV, announced plans in May 2021 to build a 40-stall truck stop/charging station in Bakersfield, California.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] At full capacity, it was slated to provide a combined 25 MW of charging power, partially drawn from an on-site solar array and battery storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Common connectors include Type 1 (Yazaki), Type 2 (Mennekes), CCS Combo 1 and 2, CHAdeMO, and Tesla.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In India, "low-power" vehicles with traction battery voltages less than 100 V DC use the Bharat EV Charger standards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] For AC charging (230 V, 15 A / 10 kW maximum), the Bharat EV Charger AC-001 standard endorses the IEC 60309 three-pin connector.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] For DC charging (48–72+ V, 200 A / 15 kW maximum), the corresponding Bharat EV Charger DC-001 standard endorses the same connector used in China (GB/T 20234.3).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] For high-power vehicles, India has largely adopted global standards: IEC 62196 Type 2 connector for AC charging (≥22 kW) and CHAdeMO and CCS Combo 2 for DC charging (≥50 kW).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Although GB/T 20234.2 is physically capable of supporting three-phase power, the standard does not include its use; as such, the implementation is limited to single-phase.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] CCS DC charging requires power-line communication (PLC).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Two connectors are added at the bottom of Type 1 or Type 2 vehicle inlets and charging plugs to supply DC current.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] These are commonly known as Combo 1 or Combo 2 connectors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The choice of style inlets is normally standardized on a per-country basis so that public chargers do not need to fit cables with both variants.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Generally, North America uses Combo 1 style vehicle inlets, while most of the rest of the world uses Combo 2.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The CHAdeMO standard is favored by Nissan, Mitsubishi, and Toyota, while the SAE J1772 Combo standard is backed by GM, Ford, Volkswagen, BMW, and Hyundai.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Both systems charge to 80% in approximately 20 minutes, but the two systems are incompatible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In the United States, many of the EVs first marketed in the late 1990s and early 2000s such as the GM EV1, Ford Ranger EV, and Chevrolet S-10 EV preferred the use of Level 2 (single-phase AC) EVSE, as defined under NEC-1999, to maintain acceptable charging speed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] These EVSEs were fitted with either an inductive connector (Magne Charge) or a conductive connector (generally AVCON).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Proponents of the inductive system were GM, Nissan, and Toyota; DaimlerChrysler, Ford, and Honda backed the conductive system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Magne Charge paddles were available in two different sizes: an older, larger paddle (used for the EV1 and S-10 EV) and a newer, smaller paddle (used for the first-generation Toyota RAV4 EV, but backwards compatible with large-paddle vehicles through an adapter).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The larger paddle (introduced in 1994) was required to accommodate a liquid-cooled vehicle inlet charge port; the smaller paddle (introduced in 2000) interfaced with an air-cooled inlet instead.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] SAE J1773, which described the technical requirements for inductive paddle coupling, was first issued in January 1995, with another revision issued in November 1999.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The influential California Air Resources Board adopted the conductive connector as its standard on 28 June 2001, based on lower costs and durability, and the Magne Charge paddle was discontinued by the following March.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Three conductive connectors existed at the time, named according to their manufacturers: Avcon (aka butt-and-pin, used by Ford, Solectria, and Honda); Yazaki (aka pin-and-sleeve, on the RAV4 EV); and ODU (used by DaimlerChrysler).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] IWC recommended the Avcon butt connector for North America, based on environmental and durability testing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As implemented, the Avcon connector used four contacts for Level 2 (L1, L2, Pilot, Ground) and added five more (three for serial communications, and two for DC power) for Level 3 (L1, L2, Pilot, Com1, Com2, Ground, Clean Data ground, DC+, DC−).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] By 2009, J1772 had instead adopted the round pin-and-sleeve (Yazaki) connector as its standard implementation, and the rectangular Avcon butt connector was rendered obsolete.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging time depends on the battery's capacity, power density, and charging power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The larger the capacity, the more charge the battery can hold (analogous to the size of a fuel tank).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Higher power density allows the battery to accept more charge per unit time (the size of the tank opening).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Higher charging power supplies more energy per unit time (analogous to a pump's flow rate).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] An important downside of charging at fast speeds is that it also adds stress to the mains electricity grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The California Air Resources Board specified a target minimum range of 150 miles (240 km) to qualify as a zero-emission vehicle, and further specified that the vehicle should allow for fast-charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The effective charging power can be lower than the maximum charging power due to limitations of the battery or battery management system, charging losses (which can be as high as 25%), and vary over time due to charging limits applied by a charge controller.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In early 2025, two Chinese companies announced battery technology to enable electric vehicles to drive long distances on a five-minute charge.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] BYD developed a battery with a peak charging capacity of 1,000 kW (1 MW), compared to US chargers then having peak rates of 400 kW or less.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] China's grid infrastructure allows high-power charging hubs to be connected directly to the power grid—sometimes even to high-voltage lines—avoiding the delay of local utility upgrades in the US.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The usable battery capacity of a first-generation electric vehicle, such as the original Nissan Leaf, was about 20 kilowatt-hours (kWh), giving it a range of about 100 mi (160 km).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla was the first company to introduce longer-range vehicles, initially releasing their Model S with battery capacities of 40 kWh, 60 kWh and 85 kWh, with the latter lasting for about 480 km (300 mi).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of 2022 plug-in hybrid vehicles typically had an electric range of 15 to 60 miles (24–97 km).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] To charge from the AC power supplied by the electrical grid, EVs have a small AC-to-DC converter built into the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The charging cable supplies AC power directly from the grid, and the vehicle converts this power to DC internally and charges its battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The built-in converters on most EVs typically support charging speeds up to 6–7 kW, sufficient for overnight charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] To facilitate rapid recharging of EVs, much higher power (50–100+ kW) is necessary.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This requires a much larger AC-to-DC converter which is not practical to integrate into the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Instead, the AC-to-DC conversion is performed by the charging station, and DC power is supplied to the vehicle directly, bypassing the built-in converter.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations are usually accessible to multiple electric vehicles and are equipped with current or connection sensing mechanisms to disconnect the power when the EV is not charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Sensor wires react more quickly, have fewer parts to fail, and are possibly less expensive to design and implement.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Current sensors however can use standard connectors and can allow suppliers to monitor or charge for the electricity actually consumed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Longer drives require a network of public charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In addition, they are essential for vehicles that lack access to a home charging station, as is common in multi-family housing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Costs vary greatly by country, power supplier, and power source.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some services charge by the minute, while others charge by the amount of energy received (measured in kilowatt-hours).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In the United States, some states have banned the use of charging by kWh.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations may not need much new infrastructure in developed countries, less than delivering a new fuel over a new network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The stations can leverage the existing ubiquitous electrical grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations are offered by public authorities, commercial enterprises, and some major employers to address a range of barriers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Options include simple charging posts for roadside use, charging cabinets for covered parking places, and fully automated charging stations integrated with power distribution equipment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of December 2012, around 50,000 non-residential charging points were deployed in the US, Europe, Japan and China.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of August 2014, some 3,869 CHAdeMO quick chargers were deployed, with 1,978 in Japan, 1,181 in Europe and 686 in the United States, and 24 in other countries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of December 2021 the total number of public and private EV charging stations was over 57,000 in the United States and Canada combined.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of May 2023, there are over 3.9 million public EV charging points worldwide, with Europe having over 600,000, China leading with over 2.7 million.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] United States has over 138,100 charging outlets for plug-in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In January 2023, S&P Global Mobility estimated that the US has about 126,500 Level 2 and 20,431 Level 3 charging stations, plus another 16,822 Tesla Superchargers and Tesla destination chargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This follows the 17,000 public charging stations that existed in 2012, mostly built by the State Grid of China as a pilot program in major cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou, Shenzhen and Hefei.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of December 2012, Japan had 1,381 public DC fast-charging stations, the largest deployment of fast chargers in the world, but only around 300 AC chargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of September 2013, the largest public charging networks in Australia were in the capital cities of Perth and Melbourne, with around 30 stations (7 kW AC) established in both cities – smaller networks exist in other capital cities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] By 2024, the public charging network in Perth had grown to over 209 chargers while nationally there are over 5000 chargers across Australia as of 2026.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In India, public electric vehicle (EV) charging stations are commonly located street-side and at retail shopping centers, government facilities, and other parking areas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Private charging stations are typically found at residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of December 2013, Estonia was the only country that had completed the deployment of an EV charging network with nationwide coverage, with 165 fast chargers available along highways at a maximum distance of between 40–60 km (25–37 mi), and a higher density in urban areas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of November 2012, about 15,000 charging stations had been installed in Europe.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of March 2013, Norway had 4,029 charging points and 127 DC fast-charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As part of its commitment to environmental sustainability, the Dutch government initiated a plan to establish over 200 fast (DC) charging stations across the country by 2015.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The rollout will be undertaken by ABB and Dutch startup Fastned, aiming to provide at least one station every 50 km (31 mi) for the Netherlands' 16 million residents.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In addition to that, the E-laad foundation installed about 3000 public (slow) charge points since 2009.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Compared to other markets, such as China, the European electric car market has developed slowly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This, together with the lack of charging stations, has reduced the number of electric models available in Europe.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2018 and 2019 the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed several projects with companies like Allego, Greenway, BeCharge and Enel X.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The EIB loans will support the deployment of the charging station infrastructure with a total of €200 million.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The UK government declared that it will ban the selling of new petrol and diesel vehicles by 2035 for a complete shift towards electric charging vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of August 2018, 800,000 electric vehicles and 18,000 charging stations operated in the United States, up from 5,678 public charging stations and 16,256 public charging points in 2013.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of October 2023, in the US and Canada, there are 6,502 stations with CHAdeMO connectors, 7,480 stations with SAE CCS1 connectors, and 7,171 stations with Tesla North American Charging System (NACS) connectors, according to the US Department of Energy's Alternative Fuels Data Center.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of March 2026, there are 78,444 EV charging stations with 241,301 chargers across the United States.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] California has the highest number of all the states and also has the most EVs registered..
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Shopping centers have 95% of all fast DC chargers making them appropriate for quick fueling while 90% at hotels are the slower level 2 units.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Colder areas in northern US states and Canada have some public power receptacles, primarily for use by block heaters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Although their circuit breakers prevent large current draws for other uses, they can be used to recharge electric vehicles, albeit slowly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In public lots, some such outlets are turned on only when the temperature falls below −30 °C (−22 °F), thus limiting their use for charging EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In June 2022, United States President Biden announced a plan for a standardized nationwide network of 500,000 electric vehicle charging stations by 2030 that will be agnostic to EV brands, charging companies, or location, in the United States.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The US will provide US$5 billion between 2022 and 2026 to states through the National Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (NEVI) Formula Program to build charging stations along major highways and corridors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] One such proposed corridor called Greenlane plans to establish charging infrastructure between Los Angeles, California and Las Vegas, Nevada.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In April 2025, the flagship charging station was operational in Colton, California, with further locations in Barstow and Baker, under development.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In July 2023, automakers General Motors, BMW, Honda, Hyundai, Kia, Mercedes, and Stellantis announced they were building a North American network of fast-chargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Toyota would later join, and the venture was named Ionna.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of late 2023, a limited number of Tesla Superchargers started to open to non-Tesla vehicles through the use of a built in CCS adapter for existing superchargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Other charging networks available for all electric vehicles include Electrify America, EVgo, and ChargePoint.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In October 2023, Electrify America announced 15 agreements with various automakers for their electric vehicles to use its network of chargers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In May 2025, Tesla announced plans to develop a public, 46-station Megacharger network to support deployments of the Tesla Semi at ACT Expo.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] South Africa has a small, but expanding network of charging stations, and a growing number of EVs and PHEVs on the road.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] There is no direct government infrastructure spending on EV charging, and SA therefore has a patchwork of private charging sites.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Investment in infrastructure is increasing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] There are already proof of concept high-capacity DC chargers installed at various sites across SA, including the three 400 kW chargers at Charge's N12 North West facility, the 200 kW station at the Mall of Africa in Midrand, and the 150 kW one at Canal Walk in Cape Town.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The cost of installing a charging station is estimated to be between R500,0000 and R2 million.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] To reach profitability, SA will need around 100,000 EVs on the road.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of 2025, there are around 3,500 new EVs sold per year in South Africa.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Sales are expected to grow steadily, as new models are introduced into the market.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] At the same time, the industry was estimated to already be worth R2.8 billion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] There are plans to build around more charging stations over the next few years.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Companies included in these developments are Eskom, BYD, the National Automobile Association of South Africa, and Cape Town-based Charge, with its solar-powered passenger vehicle and electric truck charging stations, as part of a R100 million investment from the Development Bank of Southern Africa).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In April 2017 YPF, the state-owned oil company of Argentina, reported that it will install 220 fast-load stations for electric vehicles in 110 of its service stations in the national territory.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Electric car manufacturers, charging infrastructure providers, and regional governments have entered into agreements and ventures to promote and provide electric vehicle networks of public charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The EV Plug Alliance is an association of 21 European manufacturers that proposed an IEC norm and a European standard for sockets and plugs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Members (Schneider Electric, Legrand, Scame, Nexans, etc.) claimed that the system was safer because they use shutters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Prior consensus was that the IEC 62196 and IEC 61851-1 standards have already established safety by making parts non-live when touchable.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Over 80% of electric vehicle charging is done at home, usually in a garage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In North America, Level 1 charging is connected to a standard 120 volt outlet and provides less than 5 miles (8.0 km) of range per hour of charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] To address the need for faster charging, Level 2 charging stations have become more prevalent.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] These stations operate at 240 volts and can significantly increase the charging speed, delivering up to more than 30 miles (48 km) of range per hour.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Level 2 chargers offer a more practical solution for EV owners, especially for those who have higher daily mileage requirements.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations can be installed using two main methods: hardwired connections to the main electrical panel box or through a cord and plug connected to a 240-volt receptacle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A popular choice for the latter is the NEMA 14-50 receptacle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This type of outlet provides 240 volts and, when wired to a 50-ampere circuit, can support charging at 40 amperes according to North American electrical code.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This translates to a power supply of up to 9.6 kilowatts, offering a faster and more efficient charging experience.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A battery swapping (or switching) station allow vehicles to exchange a discharged battery pack for a charged one, eliminating the charge interval.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Battery swapping is common in electric forklift applications.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The concept of an exchangeable battery service was proposed as early as 1896.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] It was first offered between 1910 and 1924, by Hartford Electric Light Company, through the GeVeCo battery service, serving electric trucks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The vehicle owner purchased the vehicle, without a battery, from General Vehicle Company (GeVeCo), part-owned by General Electric.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The power was purchased from Hartford Electric in the form of an exchangeable battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Both vehicles and batteries were designed to facilitate a fast exchange.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The owner paid a variable per-mile charge and a monthly service fee to cover truck maintenance and storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] These vehicles covered more than 6 million miles (9.7 million kilometres).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Beginning in 1917, a similar service operated in Chicago for owners of Milburn Light Electric cars.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] 91 years later, a rapid battery replacement system was implemented to service 50 electric buses at the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Better Place, Tesla, and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries considered battery switch approaches.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] One complicating factor was that the approach requires vehicle design modifications.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2012, Tesla started building a proprietary fast-charging Tesla Supercharger network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2013, Tesla announced it would also support battery pack swaps.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A demonstration swapping station was built at Harris Ranch and operated for a short period of time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] However customers vastly preferred using the Superchargers, so the swapping program was shut down.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The Better Place network was the first modern attempt at the battery switching model.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The Renault Fluence Z.E. was the first car enabled to adopt the approach and was offered in Israel and Denmark.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Better Place launched its first battery-swapping station in Israel, in Kiryat Ekron, near Rehovot in March 2011.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Better Place filed for bankruptcy in Israel in May 2013.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In June 2013, Tesla announced its plan to offer battery swapping.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla showed that a battery swap with the Model S took just over 90 seconds.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Elon Musk said the service would be offered at around US$60 to US$80 at June 2013 prices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The vehicle purchase included one battery pack.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] After a swap, the owner could later return and receive their battery pack fully charged.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A second option would be to keep the swapped battery and receive/pay the difference in value between the original and the replacement.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2015 the company abandoned the idea for lack of customer interest.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] By 2022, Chinese luxury carmaker Nio had built more than 900 battery swap stations across China and Europe, up from 131 in 2020.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Unlike filling stations, which need to be located near roads that tank trucks can enter conveniently, charging stations can theoretically be placed anywhere with access to electric power and adequate parking.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Private locations include residences, workplaces, and hotels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Residences are by far the most common charging location.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Residential charging stations typically lack user authentication and separate metering, and may require a dedicated circuit.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Many vehicles being charged at residences simply use a cable that plugs into a standard household electrical outlet.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Public stations have been sited along highways, in shopping centers, hotels, government facilities and at workplaces.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some gas stations offer EV charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some charging stations have been criticized as inaccessible, hard to find, out of order, and slow, thus slowing EV adoption.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Public charge stations may charge a fee or offer free service based on government or corporate promotions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charge rates vary from residential rates for electricity to many times higher.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The premium is usually for the convenience of faster charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Vehicles can typically be charged without the owner present, allowing the owner to partake in other activities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Sites include malls, freeway rest areas, transit stations, and government offices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Typically, AC Type 1/Type 2 plugs are used.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Wireless charging uses inductive charging mats that charge without a wired connection and can be embedded in parking stalls or even on roadways.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Mobile charging involves another vehicle that brings the charge station to the electric vehicle; the power is supplied via a fuel generator (typically gasoline or diesel), or a large battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] An offshore electricity recharging system named Stillstrom, to be launched by Danish shipping firm Maersk Supply Service, will give ships access to renewable energy while at sea.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Connecting ships to electricity generated by offshore wind farms, Stillstrom is designed to cut emissions from idling ships.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] A smart grid is a power grid that can adapt to changing conditions by limiting service or adjusting prices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some charging stations can communicate with the grid and activate charging when conditions are optimal, such as when prices are relatively low.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some vehicles allow the operator to control recharging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Vehicle-to-grid scenarios allow the vehicle battery to supply the grid during periods of peak demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This requires communication between the grid, charging station, and vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] SAE International is developing related standards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] ISO and IEC are developing similar standards known as ISO/IEC 15118, which also provide protocols for automatic payment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Electric vehicles (EVs) can be powered by renewable energy sources like wind, solar, hydropower, geothermal, biogas, and some low-impact hydroelectric sources.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Renewable energy sources are generally less expensive, cleaner, and more sustainable than non-renewable sources like coal, natural gas, and petroleum power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Charging stations are powered by whatever the power grid runs on, which might include oil, coal, and natural gas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] However, many companies have been making advancements towards clean energy for their charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of November 2023, Electrify America has invested over $5 million to develop over 50 solar-powered electric vehicle (EV) charging stations in rural California, including areas like Fresno County.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] These resilient Level 2 (L2) stations aren't tied to the electrical grid, and they provide drivers in rural areas access to EV charging via renewable resources.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Electrify America’s Solar Glow 1 project, a 75-megawatt solar power initiative in San Bernardino County, is expected to generate 225,000 megawatt-hours of clean electricity annually, enough to power over 20,000 homes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla's Superchargers and Destination Chargers are mostly powered by solar energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Tesla's Superchargers have solar canopies with solar panels that generate energy to offset electricity use.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Some Destination Chargers have solar panels mounted on canopies or nearby rooftops to generate energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] As of 2023, Tesla's global network was 100% renewable, achieved through a combination of onsite resources and annual renewable matching.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The E-Move Charging Station is equipped with eight monocrystalline solar panels, which can supply 1.76 kW of solar power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2012, Urban Green Energy introduced the world's first wind-powered electric vehicle charging station, the Sanya SkyPump.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The design features a 4 kW vertical-axis wind turbine paired with a GE WattStation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] In 2021, Nova Innovation introduced the world's first direct from tidal power EV charge station.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Along a section of the Highway E20 in Sweden, which connects Stockholm, Gothenburg and Malmö, a plate has been placed under the asphalt that interfaces with electric cars, recharging an electromagnetic coil receiver.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] This allows greater vehicle autonomy and reduces the size of the battery compartment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The technology is planned to be implemented along 3,000 km of Swedish roads.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] Sweden's first electrified stretch of road, and the world's first permanent one, connects the Hallsberg and Örebro area.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/charging-station] The work is scheduled for completion by 2025.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] An **electric vehicle** (**EV**) is a vehicle propelled mostly by electric power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs encompass road (cars, buses, trucks and personal transporters), rail (trains, trams and monorails), boats and submersibles, aircraft (fixed-wing and multirotors) and spacecraft.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs originated in the late 19th century.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electricity was among the preferred methods for powering early motor vehicles because it was quieter, provided comfort, and ease of operation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, its limited range hindered mass adoption throughout the 20th century.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Since the late 20th century, technological advances in lithium batteries—which offer superior energy density and current output versus lead-acid batteries—has revived public interest as zero-emission vehicle options.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Manufacturers mostly switched to hybrids that use internal combustion engines like conventional vehicles, but add electric motors as a supplement, powered by electricity produced internally by motor-generators and recovered from regenerative braking.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Although spacecraft have been propelled by electricity since the 1960s, non-rocket spacelaunch from Earth remains science fiction.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] As a means of reducing tailpipe emissions of greenhouse gases and other air pollutants, and to reduce the dependency on fossil fuels, government incentives are also available in many areas to promote the adoption of electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] As of 2026, the electric vehicle industry in China produces more than the rest of the world combined.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In January 1990 General Motors President introduced its EV concept two-seater, the "Impact", at the Los Angeles Auto Show.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] That September, the California Air Resources Board mandated major-automaker sales of EVs, in phases starting in 1998.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] From 1996 to 1998 GM produced 1117 EV1s, 800 of which were made available through three-year leases.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Chrysler, Ford, GM, Honda, and Toyota also produced limited numbers of EVs for California drivers during this period.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2003, upon the expiration of GM's EV1 leases, GM discontinued them.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A movie made on the subject in 2005–2006 was titled *Who Killed the Electric Car?* and released theatrically by Sony Pictures Classics in 2006.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The film explores the roles of automobile manufacturers, oil industry, the U.S. government, batteries, hydrogen vehicles, and the general public, and each of their roles in limiting the deployment and adoption of this technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Ford released a number of their Ford Ecostar delivery vans into the market.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Honda, Nissan and Toyota also repossessed and crushed most of their EVs, which, like the GM EV1s, had been available only by closed-end lease.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] After public protests, Toyota sold 200 of its RAV4 EVs; they later sold at over their original forty-thousand-dollar price.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Later, BMW of Canada sold off a number of Mini EVs when their Canadian testing ended.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The production of the Citroën Berlingo Electrique stopped in September 2005.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Zenn started production in 2006 but ended by 2009.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The global stock of both plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEVs) and battery electric vehicles (BEVs) has grown steadily since the 2010s.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] During the late 20th and early 21st century, the environmental impact of the petroleum-based transportation infrastructure, along with the fear of peak oil, led to renewed interest in electric transportation infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] By the 21st century an energy transition to electrify as many things as possible, not just vehicles, rather than burning stuff became to be seen as very important for human health and the environment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs differ from fossil fuel-powered vehicles in that the electricity they consume can be generated from a wide range of sources, including fossil fuels, nuclear power, and renewables such as solar power and wind power, or any combination of those.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Recent advancements in battery technology and charging infrastructure have addressed many of the earlier barriers to EV adoption, making electric vehicles a more viable option for a wider range of consumers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The carbon footprint and other emissions of electric vehicles vary depending on the fuel and technology used for electricity generation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The electricity may be stored in the vehicle using a battery, flywheel, or supercapacitors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Vehicles using internal combustion engines usually only derive their energy from a single or a few sources, usually non-renewable fossil fuels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A key advantage of electric vehicles is regenerative braking, which recovers kinetic energy, typically lost during friction braking as heat, as electricity restored to the on-board battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Although over 20% of new cars sold in 2024 were electric only 2% of trucks were.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] China is the world's leading EV producer, accounting for more than 70% of global production and 67% of global sales of electric vehicles in 2024.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs are much more efficient than internal combustion engines and have few direct emissions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] At the same time, they do rely on electrical energy that is generally provided by a combination of non-fossil fuel plants and fossil fuel plants.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There are many ways to generate electricity, of varying costs, efficiency and ecological desirability.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs can be made less polluting overall by modifying the source of electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In some areas, individuals can ask utilities to provide their electricity from renewable energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Therefore, it gives the greatest degree of energy resilience.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For especially large EVs, such as submarines, the chemical energy of the diesel–electric can be replaced by a nuclear reactor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The nuclear reactor usually provides heat, which drives a steam turbine, which drives a generator, which is then fed to the propulsion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A few experimental vehicles, such as some cars and a handful of aircraft use solar panels for electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] These systems are powered from an external generator plant (nearly always when stationary), and then disconnected before motion occurs, and the electricity is stored in the vehicle until needed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Batteries, electric double-layer capacitors and flywheel energy storage are forms of rechargeable on-board electricity storage systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] By avoiding an intermediate mechanical step, the energy conversion efficiency can be improved compared to hybrids by avoiding unnecessary energy conversions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Furthermore, electro-chemical batteries conversions are reversible, allowing electrical energy to be stored in chemical form.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] An electric-vehicle battery (EVB) in addition to the traction battery specialty systems used for industrial (or recreational) vehicles, are batteries used to power the propulsion system of a battery electric vehicle (BEVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] These batteries are usually a secondary (rechargeable) battery, and are typically lithium-ion batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Traction batteries, specifically designed with a high ampere-hour capacity, are used in forklifts, electric golf carts, riding floor scrubbers, electric motorcycles, electric cars, trucks, vans, and other electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Most battery-electric vehicles also include a separate low-voltage auxiliary battery, commonly a 12-volt system, which powers accessories and control electronics.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This auxiliary battery is typically recharged from the high-voltage traction battery through a DC/DC converter.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Failures in the auxiliary-battery charging system can immobilize a vehicle even when the traction battery remains charged.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2024, Hyundai and Kia recalls cited failures of the Integrated Charging Control Unit (ICCU) that could stop charging the 12-volt battery and lead to a loss of drive power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Since their first commercial release in 1991, lithium-ion batteries have become an important technology for achieving low-carbon transportation systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Most electric vehicles use lithium-ion batteries (Li-Ions or LIBs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Lithium-ion batteries have a higher energy density, longer life span, and higher power density than most other practical batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Complicating factors include safety, durability, thermal breakdown, environmental impact, and cost.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Li-ion batteries should be used within safe temperature and voltage ranges to operate safely and efficiently.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Increasing the battery's lifespan decreases effective costs and environmental impact.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] One technique is to operate a subset of the battery cells at a time and switching these subsets.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In the past, nickel–metal hydride batteries were used in some electric cars, such as those made by General Motors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] These battery types are considered outdated due to their tendencies to self-discharge in the heat.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Furthermore, a patent for this type of battery was held by Chevron, which created a problem for their widespread development.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] These factors, coupled with their high cost, has led to lithium-ion batteries leading as the predominant battery for EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The prices of lithium-ion batteries have declined dramatically over the past decade, contributing to a reduction in price for electric vehicles, but an increase in the price of critical minerals such as lithium from 2021 to the end of 2022 has put pressure on historical battery price decreases.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The power of a vehicle's electric motor, as in other machines, is measured in kilowatts (kW).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric motors can deliver their maximum torque over a wide RPM range.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This means that the performance of a vehicle with a 100 kW electric motor exceeds that of a vehicle with a 100 kW internal combustion engine, which can only deliver its maximum torque within a limited range of engine speed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Efficiency of charging varies considerably depending on the type of charger, and energy is lost during the process of converting the electrical energy to mechanical energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Usually, direct current (DC) electricity is fed into a DC/AC inverter where it is converted to alternating current (AC) electricity and this AC electricity is connected to a 3-phase AC motor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For electric trains, forklift trucks, and some electric cars, DC motors are often used.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In some cases, universal motors are used, and then AC or DC may be employed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In recent production vehicles, various motor types have been implemented; for instance, induction motors within Tesla vehicles and permanent magnet machines in the Nissan Leaf and Chevrolet Bolt.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric motors are mechanically very simple and often achieve 90% energy conversion efficiency over the full range of speeds and power output and can be precisely controlled.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Motion is provided by a rotary electric motor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, it is possible to "unroll" the motor to drive directly against a special matched track.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] These linear motors are used in maglev trains which float above the rails supported by magnetic levitation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This allows for almost no rolling resistance of the vehicle and no mechanical wear and tear of the train or track.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In addition to the high-performance control systems needed, switching and curving of the tracks becomes difficult with linear motors, which to date has restricted their operations to high-speed point to point services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric traction allows the use of regenerative braking, in which the motors are used as brakes and become generators that transform the motion of, usually, a train into electrical power that is then fed back into the lines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This system is particularly advantageous in mountainous operations, as descending vehicles can produce a large portion of the power required for those ascending, and in start-and-stop city use.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This regenerative system is only viable if the system is large enough to use the power generated by descending vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] They can be finely controlled and provide high torque from stationary-to-moving, unlike internal combustion engines, and do not need multiple gears to match power curves.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This removes the need for gearboxes and torque converters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs provide quiet and smooth operation and consequently have less noise and vibration than internal combustion engines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] While this is a desirable attribute, it has also evoked concern that the absence of the usual sounds of an approaching vehicle poses a danger to blind, elderly and very young pedestrians.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] To mitigate this situation, many countries mandate warning sounds when EVs are moving slowly, up to a speed when normal motion and rotation (road, suspension, electric motor, etc.) noises become audible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric motors do not require oxygen, unlike internal combustion engines; this is useful for submarines and for space rovers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] It is generally possible to equip any kind of vehicle with an electric power-train.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A pure-electric vehicle or all-electric vehicle is powered exclusively through electric motors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The electricity may come from a battery (battery electric vehicle), solar panel (solar vehicle) or fuel cell (fuel cell vehicle).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A hybrid electric vehicle (HEV) is a type of hybrid vehicle that couples a conventional internal combustion engine (ICE) with one or more electric engines into a combined propulsion system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The presence of the electric powertrain, which has inherently better energy conversion efficiency, is intended to achieve either better fuel economy or better acceleration performance than a conventional vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There is a variety of HEV types and the degree to which each functions as an electric vehicle (EV) also varies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The most common form of HEV is hybrid electric passenger cars, although hybrid electric trucks (pickups, tow trucks and tractors), buses, motorboats, and aircraft also exist.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Modern HEVs use energy recovery technologies such as motor–generator units and regenerative braking to recycle the vehicle's kinetic energy to electric energy via an alternator, which is stored in a battery pack or a supercapacitor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Some varieties of HEV use an internal combustion engine to directly drive an electrical generator, which either recharges the vehicle's batteries or directly powers the electric traction motors; this combination is known as a range extender.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Many HEVs reduce idle emissions by temporarily shutting down the combustion engine at idle (such as when waiting at the traffic light) and restarting it when needed; this is known as a start-stop system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A hybrid-electric system produces less tailpipe emissions than a comparably sized petrol engine vehicle since the hybrid's petrol engine usually has smaller displacement and thus lower fuel consumption than that of a conventional petrol-powered vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] If the engine is not used to drive the car directly, it can be geared to run at maximum efficiency, further improving fuel economy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There are different ways that a hybrid electric vehicle can combine the power from an electric motor and the internal combustion engine.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The most common type is a **parallel hybrid** that connects the engine and the electric motor to the wheels through mechanical coupling.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In this scenario, the electric motor and the engine can drive the wheels directly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] **Series hybrids** only use the electric motor to drive the wheels and can often be referred to as extended-range electric vehicles (EREVs) or range-extended electric vehicles (REEVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There are also **series–parallel hybrids** where the vehicle can be powered by the engine working alone, the electric motor on its own, or by both working together; this is designed so that the engine can run at its optimum range as often as possible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A plug-in electric vehicle (PEV) is any motor vehicle that can be recharged from any external source of electricity, such as wall sockets, and the electricity stored in the Rechargeable battery packs drives or contributes to drive the wheels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] PEV is a subcategory of electric vehicles that includes battery electric vehicles (BEVs), plug-in hybrid vehicles, (PHEVs), and electric vehicle conversions of hybrid electric vehicles and conventional internal combustion engine vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A range-extended electric vehicle (REEV) is a vehicle powered by an electric motor and a plug-in battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] An auxiliary combustion engine is used only to supplement battery charging and not as the primary source of power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] On-road electric vehicles include electric cars, electric trolleybuses, electric buses, battery electric buses, electric trucks, electric bicycles, electric motorcycles and scooters, personal transporters, neighborhood electric vehicles, golf carts, milk floats, and forklifts.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Off-road vehicles include electrified all-terrain vehicles and electric tractors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] An **electric truck** is a battery electric vehicle (BEV) designed to transport cargo, carry specialized payloads, or perform other utilitarian work.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric trucks reduce noise and pollution, relative to internal-combustion trucks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Due to the high efficiency and low component-counts of electric power trains, no fuel burning while idle, and silent and efficient acceleration, the costs of owning and operating electric trucks are dramatically lower than their predecessors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Long-distance freight has been the trucking segment least amenable to electrification, since the increased weight of batteries, relative to fuel, detracts from payload capacity, and the alternative, more frequent recharging, detracts from delivery time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] By contrast, short-haul urban delivery has been electrified rapidly, since the clean and quiet nature of electric trucks fit well with urban planning and municipal regulation, and the capacities of reasonably sized batteries are well-suited to daily stop-and-go traffic within a metropolitan area.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The fixed nature of a rail line makes it relatively easy to power EVs through permanent overhead lines or electrified third rails, eliminating the need for heavy onboard batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric locomotives, electric multiple units, electric trams (also called streetcars or trolleys), electric light rail systems, and electric rapid transit are all in common use today, especially in Europe and Asia.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Since electric trains do not need to carry a heavy internal combustion engine or large batteries, they can have very good power-to-weight ratios.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This allows high speed trains such as France's double-deck TGVs to operate at speeds of 320 km/h (200 mph) or higher, and electric locomotives to have a much higher power output than diesel locomotives.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In addition, they have higher short-term surge power for fast acceleration, and using regenerative brakes can put braking power back into the electrical grid rather than wasting it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Maglev trains are also nearly always EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There are also battery electric passenger trains operating on non-electrified rail lines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Particularly in Europe, fuel-cell electric trains are gaining in popularity to replace diesel–electric locomotive units.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In Germany, several Länder have ordered Alstom Coradia iLINT trainsets, in service since 2018, with France also planning to order trainsets.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The United Kingdom, the Netherlands, Denmark, Norway, Italy, Canada and Mexico are equally interested.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In France, the SNCF plans to replace all its remaining diesel-electric trains with hydrogen trains by 2035.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In the United Kingdom, Alstom announced in 2018 their plan to retrofit British Rail Class 321 trainsets with fuel cells.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric boats were popular around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Interest in quiet and potentially renewable marine transportation has steadily increased since the late 20th century, as solar cells have given motorboats the infinite range of sailboats.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric motors can and have also been used in sailboats instead of traditional diesel engines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Submarines use batteries (charged by diesel or gasoline engines at the surface), nuclear power, fuel cells or Stirling engines to run electric motor-driven propellers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Fully electric tugboats are being used in Auckland, New Zealand (June 2022), Vancouver, British Columbia (October 2023), and San Diego, California.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Since the beginnings of aviation, electric power for aircraft has received a great deal of experimentation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Currently, flying electric aircraft include piloted and unpiloted aerial vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric power has a long history of use in spacecraft.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The power sources used for spacecraft are batteries, solar panels and nuclear power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Current methods of propelling a spacecraft with electricity include the arcjet rocket, the electrostatic ion thruster, the Hall-effect thruster, and Field Emission Electric Propulsion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric vehicles are the only option for rovers as there is simply no oxygen gas to drive combustion engines in outer space and Exoplanetary atmospheres.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Crewed and uncrewed electric vehicles have been used to explore the Moon and other planets in the Solar System.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] On the last three missions of the Apollo program in 1971 and 1972, astronauts drove silver-oxide battery-powered Lunar Roving Vehicles distances up to 35.7 kilometers (22.2 mi) on the lunar surface.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Solar-powered, remotely controlled uncrewed rovers have also explored the Moon and Mars.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For this reason, most electric vehicles have a built-in AC-to-DC converter commonly known as the "onboard charger" (OBC).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Instead of recharging EVs from electric sockets, batteries could be mechanically replaced at special stations in a few minutes (battery swapping).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Batteries with greater energy density such as metal–air fuel cells cannot always be recharged in a purely electric way, so some form of mechanical recharge may be used instead.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A zinc–air battery, technically a fuel cell, is difficult to recharge electrically so may be "refueled" by periodically replacing the anode or electrolyte instead.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] General Motors (GM) is adding a capability called V2H, or bidirectional charging, to allow its new electric vehicles to send power from their batteries to the owner's home.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] GM will start with 2024 models, including the Silverado and Blazer EVs, and promises to continue the feature through to model year 2026.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This could be helpful to the owner during unexpected power grid outages because an electric vehicle is a giant battery on wheels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs release no tailpipe air pollutants, and reduce respiratory illnesses such as asthma.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] By reducing types of air pollution, such as nitrogen dioxide, EVs could also prevent hundreds of thousands of early deaths every year, especially from trucks and traffic in cities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Additionally, EVs have significantly less noise pollution in urban areas, improving the quality of life overall.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The carbon emissions from producing and operating an EV are, in the majority of cases less, than those of producing and operating a conventional vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] When pursuing a cost-responsive electric charging strategy (instead of an emission-responsive charging strategy), considerably higher emissions might arise as embedded carbon emissions from electricity are dynamic.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EVs in urban areas almost always pollute less than internal combustion vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, EVs are charged with electricity that may be generated by means that have health and environmental impacts.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This is particularly relevant in places that rely on coal-powered electricity grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] It also has negative environmental impacts due to the manufacturing and recycling of batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The full environmental impact of electric vehicles includes the life cycle impacts of carbon and sulfur emissions, as well as toxic metals entering the environment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Despite that, ICE vehicles use far more raw materials over their lifetime than EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] One source estimates that over a fifth of the lithium and about 65% of the cobalt needed for electric cars will be from recycled sources by 2035.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] On the other hand, when counting the large quantities of fossil fuel non-electric cars consume over their lifetime, electric cars can be considered to dramatically reduce raw-material needs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] One limitation of the environmental potential of EVs is that simply switching the existing privately owned car fleet from ICEs to EVs will not free up road space for active travel or public transport.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric micromobility vehicles, such as e-bikes, may contribute to the decarbonisation of transport systems, especially outside of urban areas which are already well-served by public transport.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Information regarding the sustainability of the production process of batteries has become a politically charged topic.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Business processes of raw material extraction in practice raise issues of transparency and accountability of the management of extractive resources.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In the complex supply chain of lithium technology, there are diverse stakeholders representing corporate interests, public interest groups and political elites that are concerned with outcomes from the technology production and use.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] One possibility to achieve balanced extractive processes would be the establishment of commonly agreed-upon standards on the governance of technology worldwide.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The compliance of these standards can be assessed by the Assessment of Sustainability in Supply Chains Frameworks (ASSC).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Hereby, the qualitative assessment consists of examining governance and social and environmental commitment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Indicators for the quantitative assessment are management systems and standards, compliance and social and environmental indicators.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The initial phase of electric vehicle production incurs an environmental cost, often referred to as a "carbon debt", primarily driven by the energy-intensive manufacturing of high-voltage batteries and the extraction of critical raw materials.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Rare-earth metals (neodymium, dysprosium) and other mined metals (copper, nickel, iron) are used by EV motors, while lithium, cobalt, manganese are used by the batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2023 the US State Department said that the supply of lithium would need to increase 42-fold by 2050 globally to support a transition to clean energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Most of the lithium-ion battery production occurs in China, where the bulk of energy used is supplied by coal-burning power plants.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The extraction and processing of these metals contributes to habitat destruction and environmental degradation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For instance, the process of mining minerals such as lithium and cobalt, essential components of current battery chemistries, carries significant localized environmental hazards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Lithium mining, frequently conducted using water-intensive brine extraction, contributes to global carbon emissions, estimated at over 1.3 million tonnes of carbon annually, with every tonne of mined lithium equating to 15 tonnes of CO2 released into the atmosphere.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In regions rich in cobalt, such as the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), environmental costs are substantial, including deforestation, habitat destruction and water pollution.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Scientists have noted high radioactivity levels in some mining regions, and industrial processes, including the pulverization of rock, release dust that causes respiratory health issues for nearby populations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Open-pit nickel mining has led to environmental degradation and pollution in developing countries such as the Philippines and Indonesia.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2024, nickel mining and processing was one of the main causes of deforestation in Indonesia.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2023, Greenpeace issued a video criticizing the view that EVs are "silver bullet for climate", arguing that the construction phase has a high environmental impact.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For example, the rise in SUV sales by Hyundai almost eliminate the climate benefits of passing to EV in this company, because even electric SUVs have a high carbon footprint as they consume much raw materials and energy during construction.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Greenpeace proposes a mobility as a service concept instead, based on biking, public transport and ride sharing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Despite the initial manufacturing footprint, a life-cycle assessment (LCA) approach consistently confirms that electric vehicles yield superior overall lifetime greenhouse gas (GHG) performance compared to equivalent ICE vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The extent of the environmental benefit is intrinsically linked to the carbon intensity of the electricity grid used to power the vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In regions like China, battery electric vehicles currently achieve approximately 40% lower emissions compared to ICE vehicles over their full lifespan.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, in countries with high-intensity grids, such as India, the immediate advantage is more modest, resulting in only about 20% lower emissions (saving less than 10 tonnes of CO2 equivalent).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This context is temporary, as significant efforts are underway globally to decarbonize electricity generation; for instance, the emissions intensity of India's grid is projected to fall by 60% by 2035, rapidly increasing the environmental benefit of electrification.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] An alternative method of sourcing essential battery materials being deliberated by the International Seabed Authority is deep sea mining, however carmakers are not using this as of 2023.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Regulatory mechanisms, such as the EU Battery Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2023/1542) were introduced to reduce the environmental impact.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] It covers the entire battery life cycle, from design and production, "battery passports", to use and end-of-life management.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] There are also national policies like those in France, which cap subsidies based on vehicle production carbon intensity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] EV 'tank-to-wheels' efficiency is about a factor of three higher than internal combustion engine vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Energy is not consumed while the vehicle is stationary, unlike internal combustion engines which consume fuel while idling.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] In 2022, EVs enabled a net reduction of about 80 Mt of GHG emissions, on a well-to-wheels basis, and the net GHG benefit of EVs will increase over time as the electricity sector is decarbonised.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Well-to-wheel efficiency of an EV has less to do with the vehicle itself and more to do with the method of electricity production.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A particular EV would instantly become twice as efficient if electricity production were switched from fossil fuels to renewable energy, such as wind power, tidal power, solar power, and nuclear power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Thus, when "well-to-wheels" is cited, the discussion is no longer about the vehicle, but rather about the entire energy supply infrastructure – in the case of fossil fuels this should also include energy spent on exploration, mining, refining, and distribution.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The lifecycle analysis of EVs shows that even when powered by the most carbon-intensive electricity in Europe, they emit less greenhouse gases than a conventional diesel vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric vehicles may have shorter range compared to vehicles with internal combustion engines, which is why the electrification of long-distance transport, such as long-distance shipping, remains challenging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] As of 2025 practical electric aircraft are small and limited to a few hundred kilometres.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric vehicles with low worldwide market share, such as ships, typically carry a higher initial purchase price than comparable ICE vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This elevated upfront cost constitutes a significant barrier to entry.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] While long-term financial analyses may favor EVs, the immediate capital outlay often dictates purchasing decisions, slowing the pace of the overall market transition.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The higher initial price is often offset by superior total cost of ownership (TCO) over the vehicle's lifespan.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Operational expenses for EVs are markedly lower.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Advances in lithium-ion batteries, driven at first by the personal-use electronics industry, allow full-sized, highway-capable EVs to travel nearly as far on a single charge as conventional cars go on a single tank of gasoline.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Lithium batteries have been made safe, can be recharged in minutes instead of hours (see recharging time), and now last longer than the typical vehicle (see lifespan).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The production cost of these lighter, higher-capacity lithium-ion batteries is gradually decreasing as the technology matures and production volumes increase.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Research is also underway to improve battery reuse and recycling, which would further reduce the environmental impact of batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Many companies and researchers are also working on newer battery technologies, including solid state batteries and alternate technologies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The risk of requiring an out-of-warranty battery replacement represents the greatest source of long-term financial uncertainty for many prospective EV retail owners.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Despite consumer anxieties, actual battery replacement events are statistically rare, and modern EV batteries are demonstrating significantly greater durability than initially anticipated.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Studies have confirmed that EV batteries can outlast the vehicle's lifetime with minimal degradation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The financial risk associated with future replacement is collapsing due to advancements in battery manufacturing and economics.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Industry reports project that global market oversupply will persist through 2028, accelerating price reductions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric vehicle range and battery performance are negatively affected by extreme cold, as ambient temperatures necessitate diverting energy for cabin heating and maintaining optimal battery temperature.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A comprehensive winter performance study by the Canadian Automobile Association (CAA) revealed that cold weather significantly impacts driving range, with vehicles experiencing reductions between 14% and 39% compared to their official estimates when operated at −15∘C.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] This quantifiable range loss presents a significant practical challenge for owners in cold climates.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, as the industry matures, increasing standardization and optimization of these thermal systems are expected to mitigate cold weather range anxiety.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] A heat pump system, capable of cooling the cabin during summer and heating it during winter, is an efficient way of heating and cooling EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] For vehicles which are connected to the grid, battery EVs can be preheated, or cooled, with little or no need for battery energy, especially for short trips.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Most new electric cars come with heat pumps as standard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Electric vehicle safety regulations have evolved significantly since the initial UN ECE Regulation 100.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Current regulations focus on thermal runaway protection, with various international standards mandating advance warning systems and thermal propagation containment measures.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Recent technological developments address thermal runaway concerns more proactively.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Advanced fire protection materials for EV batteries have become a critical research area, with developments in ceramics, mica, aerogels, coatings, and phase change materials designed to prevent or delay thermal runaway propagation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Current regulations vary by region, with China being an early adopter of thermal runaway-specific requirements mandating prevention of fire or smoke exiting battery packs for five minutes after an event occurs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] However, industry experts suggest longer escape times may be necessary for future regulations, with original equipment manufacturers targeting extended protection periods to pre-empt future regulatory requirements.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Research published in the British Medical Journal indicates that electric cars hit pedestrians at twice the rate of petrol or diesel vehicles due to being quieter.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The infrastructure for vehicle repairs after accidents is a concern for insurers and mechanics due to safety requirements.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Although no fatalities have been reported in electric vehicle repair till year 2024, repairing the high voltage battery includes electrical injury, arc flash and fire hazard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Batteries and other components must be carefully evaluated rather than being totally written off by insurers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The transport planner, Karel Martens, in a 2009 article warned that electric vehicles only solve the problem of emissions by cars while not solving or improving their impact on the amount of space used by cars or parking issues.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Martens who is of the field of Transport Justice, also said that electric vehicles do not improve accessibility to people who do not own cars.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] The IEA suggests that taxing inefficient internal combustion engine vehicles could encourage adoption of EVs, with taxes raised being used to fund subsidies for EVs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Government procurement is sometimes used to encourage national EV manufacturers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Many countries will ban sales of fossil fuel road vehicles between 2025 and 2040.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Many governments offer incentives to promote the use of electric vehicles, with the goals of reducing air pollution and oil consumption.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Some incentives intend to increase purchases of electric vehicles by offsetting the purchase price with a grant.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Other incentives include lower tax rates or exemption from certain taxes, and investment in charging infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] As of 2025 most European countries offer financial incentives to encourage commercial EV adoption.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Partnerships between EV manufacturers and utility companies have also provided incentives and sales on EV purchases to promote cleaner energy usage and transportation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p01] Companies selling EVs have partnered with local electric utilities to provide large incentives on some electric vehicles.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] With the increase in number of electric vehicles, it is necessary to create an appropriate number of charging stations to supply the increasing demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] While the deployment of public charging infrastructure is accelerating globally, the adoption rate of EVs risks outpacing network expansion, leading to potential future congestion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Experts concur that large-scale EV adoption will inevitably stress local distribution networks if charging is conducted randomly during peak hours of electricity demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] This unmanaged demand risks grid instability and necessitates proactive management from utilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] In the United States, charging ports saw quarterly increases between 4.6% and 6.3% in early 2024.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] However, projections indicate a measurable risk of insufficient density.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] In the US, the ratio of electric light-duty vehicles per public charging point is projected to climb dramatically from approximately 18:1 in 2023 to over 80:1 by 2035.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] This sharply increasing ratio confirms that current deployment, while active, may be structurally insufficient to prevent charging queues unless aggressive government targets, such as the US objective of 500,000 public charging ports by 2030, are met and exceeded.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Policy mandates are driving targeted deployment to alleviate infrastructure pressure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Countries like India have set requirements for installing chargers every 25 km along major highways.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Logistical hurdles regarding charge times are being addressed by rapid advancements in charging technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Commercially available DC fast charging stations currently deliver 250–350 kW, and regulatory frameworks, such as the EU's Alternative Fuels Infrastructure Regulation (AFIR), are preparing for the eventual commercialization of 1 MW charging stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The transition to 1 MW charging, however, requires significant investment in both installation and grid upgrades.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] This vehicle-to-grid (V2G) connection has the potential to reduce the need for new power plants, as long as vehicle owners do not mind reducing the life of their batteries, by being drained by the power company during peak demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Electric vehicle parking lots can provide demand response.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Current electricity infrastructure may need to cope with increasing shares of variable-output power sources such as wind and solar.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] This variability could be addressed by adjusting the speed at which EV batteries are charged, or possibly even discharged.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Some concepts see battery exchanges and battery charging stations, much like gas/petrol stations today.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] These will require enormous storage and charging potentials, which could be manipulated to vary the rate of charging, and to output power during shortage periods, much as diesel generators are used for short periods to stabilize some national grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Conventional electric double-layer capacitors (supercapacitors) continue to be developed to achieve higher energy densities while maintaining their characteristic fast charging capabilities and extended lifespans.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Recent research has focused on solid-state supercapacitor configurations that eliminate liquid electrolytes, providing enhanced safety and design flexibility.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Advanced developments include all-graphene oxide flexible solid-state supercapacitors with enhanced electrochemical performance, achieving areal capacitances of 14.5 mF cm⁻² among the highest values for any graphene-based supercapacitor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] High-performance solid-state supercapacitors have been developed using silicon electrodes with graphene interconnected networks, showing remarkable performance characteristics comparable to high-power carbon-based supercapacitors.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Advanced hybrid designs include all-solid-state planar micro-supercapacitors based on 2D vanadium nitride nanosheets and cobalt hydroxide nanoflowers, achieving energy densities of 12.4 mWh cm⁻³ and power densities of 1,750 mW cm⁻³.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Flexible solid-state supercapacitors operating across wide temperature ranges from -70 °C to 220 °C have been demonstrated using polycation-polybenzimidazole blend electrolytes doped with phosphoric acid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The Fraunhofer ISI Solid-State Battery Roadmap 2035+, developed with contributions from more than 100 European experts, provides a comprehensive assessment of solid-state battery development potential over the next decade, benchmarking against established lithium-ion batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] According to market analysis published in Scientific Talks, solid-state batteries are projected to reach mass production with costs of 140–175 USD per kWh by 2028–2030, depending on technological and manufacturing challenges.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Recent commercial developments include Mercedes-Benz and Factorial Energy conducting road tests of semi-solid-state batteries in the EQS sedan, promising a 25% increase in range with energy densities of 391 watt-hours per kilogram.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] This represents the world's first integration of lithium-metal solid-state batteries into a production vehicle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] However, according to IEEE Spectrum analysis, solid-state batteries face significant "production hell" challenges, with experts noting pointed skepticism toward current technical announcements and the engineering obstacles that lie ahead.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Toyota continues to lead development efforts, targeting solid-state battery production by 2027–2028 with goals of 1,000 km range and 10-minute fast charging capabilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The company claims recent technological advancements have overcome previous battery life trade-offs and switched focus to mass production readiness.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Research published in ACS Energy Letters emphasizes that while all-solid-state batteries show promise for electric vehicles, significant challenges remain in Li-metal implementation, interfacial stability, and large-scale manufacturing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Sodium-ion batteries continue to show promise with potential energy densities of 400 Wh/kg and minimal expansion/contraction during charge cycles, while relying on more abundant and cost-effective materials than lithium-ion technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Recent research published in Energy & Fuels highlights sodium-ion and all-solid-state sodium batteries as promising choices for future energy storage systems due to abundant sodium resources and lower costs compared to lithium-based systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Another improvement is to decouple the electric motor from the battery through electronic control, using supercapacitors to buffer large but short power demands and regenerative braking energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The development of new cell types combined with intelligent cell management improved both weak points mentioned above.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The cell management involves not only monitoring the health of the cells but also a redundant cell configuration (one more cell than needed).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] With sophisticated switched wiring, it is possible to condition one cell while the rest are on duty.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] An electric road system (ERS) is a road which supplies electric power to vehicles travelling on it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Common implementations are overhead power lines above the road, ground-level power supply through conductive rails, and dynamic wireless power transfer (DWPT) through resonant inductive coils or inductive rails embedded in the road.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Overhead power lines are limited to commercial vehicles while ground-level rails and inductive power transfer can be used by any vehicle, which allows for public charging through a power metering and billing systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Of the three methods, ground-level conductive rails are estimated to be the most cost-effective.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Government studies and trials have been conducted in several countries seeking a national electric road system (ERS) network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Korea was the first to implement an induction-based public electric road with a commercial bus line in 2013 after testing an experimental shuttle service in 2009, but it was shut down due to aging infrastructure amidst controversy over the continued public funding of the technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] United Kingdom municipal projects in 2015 and 2021 found wireless electric roads financially unfeasible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The Swedish Transport Administration electric road program started assessing electric road systems (ERS) in 2013.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] After receiving ERS construction offers in excess of the project's budget in 2023, Sweden pursued cost-reduction measures for either wireless ERS or rail ERS.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] The project's final report, published in 2024, recommended against funding a national ERS in Sweden as it would not be cost-effective, unless the technology was adopted by its trading partners such as by France and Germany.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Following the report, the project was paused.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Germany found in 2023 that the wireless electric road system (wERS) by Electreon collects 64.3% of the transmitted energy, poses many difficulties during installation, and blocks access to other infrastructure in the road.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Germany trialed overhead lines in three projects in the 2010s and 2020s and reported they are too expensive, difficult to maintain, and pose a safety risk.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] France found similar drawbacks for overhead lines as Germany did.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] France began several electric road pilot projects in 2023 for inductive and rail systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/electric-vehicle-p02] Ground-level power supply systems are considered the most likely candidates.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, the largest form of grid storage is pumped-storage hydroelectricity, with utility-scale batteries and behind-the-meter batteries coming second and third.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are well suited for short-duration storage (under 8 hours), due to their lower cost and sensitivity to degradation at high states of charge.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries and compressed air energy storage may provide storage for medium-duration.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Two forms of storage are suited for long-duration storage: green hydrogen, produced via electrolysis and thermal energy storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage is one option to making grids more flexible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another solution is the use of more dispatchable power plants that can change their output rapidly, for instance peaking power plants to fill in supply gaps.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Demand response can shift load to other times and interconnections between regions can balance out fluctuations in renewables production.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The price of storage technologies typically goes down with experience.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, lithium-ion batteries have been getting some 20% cheaper for each doubling of worldwide capacity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Systems with under 40% variable renewables need only short-term storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] At 80%, medium-duration storage becomes essential and beyond 90%, long-duration storage does too.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging, and alternative flexibility options like demand response may be more economic.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Any electrical power grid must match electricity production to consumption, both of which vary significantly over time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy derived from solar and wind sources varies with the weather on time scales ranging from less than a second to weeks or longer.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Nuclear power is less flexible than fossil fuels, meaning it cannot easily match the variations in demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thus, low-carbon electricity without storage presents special challenges to electric utilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is one of the three key ways to replace flexibility from fossil fuels in the grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Other options are demand-side response, in which consumers change when they use electricity or how much they use.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, households may have cheaper night tariffs to encourage them to use electricity at night.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Industry and commercial consumers can also change their demand to meet supply.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Improved network interconnection smooths the variations of renewables production and demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] When there is little wind in one location, another might have a surplus of production.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Expansion of transmission lines usually takes a long time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy storage has a large set of roles in the electricity grid and can therefore provide many different services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, it can arbitrage by keeping it until the electricity price rises, it can help make the grid more stable, and help reduce investment into transmission infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The type of service provided by storage depends on who manages the technology, whether the technology is based alongside generation of electricity, within the network, or at the side of consumption.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Providing short-term flexibility is a key role for energy storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, it can help with the integration of variable renewable energy, storing it when there is an oversupply of wind and solar and electricity prices are low.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] More generally, it can exploit the changes in prices of electricity over time in the wholesale market, charging when electricity is cheap and selling when it is expensive.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can further help with grid congestion (where there is insufficient capacity on transmission lines).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Consumers can use storage to use more of their self-produced electricity (for instance from rooftop solar power).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage can also be used to provide essential grid services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the generation side, storage can smooth out the variations in production, for instance for solar and wind.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can assist in a black start after a power outage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the network side, these include frequency regulation (continuously) and frequency response (after unexpected changes in supply or demand).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] On the consumption side, storage can improve the quality of the delivered electricity in less stable grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Investment in storage may make some investments in the transmission and distribution network unnecessary, or may allow them to be scaled down.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Additionally, storage can ensure there is sufficient capacity to meet peak demand within the electricity grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, in off-grid home systems or mini-grids, electricity storage can help provide energy access in areas that were previously not connected to the electricity grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Recent advances in artificial intelligence and machine learning allow for real-time optimization of energy storage assets.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Reinforcement learning algorithms are being explored to maximize arbitrage, manage degradation, and respond to market signals, particularly in complex and high-renewable systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy from sunlight or other renewable energy is converted to potential energy for storage in devices such as electric batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The stored potential energy is later converted to electricity that is added to the power grid, even when the original energy source is not available.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In daytime, different renewable sources provide different amounts of power to the grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] At night, energy is provided by batteries that were charged during the day when renewable energy exceeded customer demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be stored directly for a short time in capacitors, somewhat longer electrochemically in batteries, and much longer chemically (e.g. hydrogen), mechanically (e.g. pumped hydropower) or as heat.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The first pumped hydroelectricity was constructed at the end of the 19th century around the Alps in Italy, Austria, and Switzerland.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technique rapidly expanded during the 1960s to 1980s nuclear boom, due to nuclear power's inability to quickly adapt to changes in electricity demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the 21st century, interest in storage surged due to the rise of sustainable energy sources, which are often weather-dependent.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Commercial batteries have been available for over a century.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, their widespread use in the power grid is more recent, with only 1 GW available in 2013.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are the most commonly used batteries for grid applications, as of 2024, following the application of batteries in electric vehicles (EVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In comparison with EVs, grid batteries require less energy density, meaning that more emphasis can be put on costs, the ability to charge and discharge often and lifespan.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This has led to a shift towards lithium iron phosphate batteries (LFP batteries), which are cheaper and last longer than traditional lithium-ion batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Costs of batteries are declining rapidly; from 2010 to 2023 costs fell by 90%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, utility-scale systems account for two thirds of added capacity, and home applications (behind-the-meter) for one third.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion batteries are highly suited to short-duration storage (<8h) due to cost and degradation associated with high states of charge.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The electric vehicle fleet has a large overall battery capacity, which can potentially be used for grid energy storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This could be in the form of vehicle-to-grid (V2G), where cars store energy when they are not in use, or by repurposing batteries from cars at the end of the vehicle's life.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Car batteries typically range between 33 and 100 kWh; for comparison, a typical upper-middle-class household in Spain might use some 18 kWh in a day.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] By 2030, batteries in electric vehicles may be able to meet all short-term storage demand globally.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been more than 100 V2G pilot projects globally.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The effect of V2G charging on battery life can be positive or negative.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Increased cycling of batteries can lead to faster degradation, but due to better management of the state of charge and gentler charging and discharging, V2G might instead increase the lifetime of batteries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Second-hand batteries may be useable for stationary grid storage for roughly 6 years, when their capacity drops from roughly 80% to 60% of the initial capacity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] LFP batteries are particularly suitable for reusing, as they degrade less than other lithium-ion batteries and recycling is less attractive as their materials are not as valuable.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In redox flow batteries, energy is stored in liquids, which are placed in two separate tanks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] When charging or discharging, the liquids are pumped into a cell with the electrodes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The amount of energy stored (as set by the size of the tanks) can be adjusted separately from the power output (as set by the speed of the pumps).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries have the advantages of low capital cost for charge-discharge duration over 4 h, and of long durability (many years).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flow batteries are inferior to lithium-ion batteries in terms of energy efficiency, averaging efficiencies between 60% and 75%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium redox batteries is most commercially advanced type of flow battery, with roughly 40 companies making them as of 2022.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Sodium-ion batteries are a possible alternative to lithium-ion batteries, as they are less flammable, and use cheaper and less critical materials.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a lower energy density, and possibly a shorter lifespan.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] If produced at the same scale as lithium-ion batteries, they may become 20% to 30% cheaper.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Iron-air batteries may be suitable for even longer duration storage than flow batteries (weeks), but the technology is not yet mature.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in supercapacitors works well for applications where a lot of power is needed for short amount of time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the power grid, they are therefore mostly used in short-term frequency regulation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Various power-to-gas and power-to-fuel technologies exist that can convert excess electricity into an easier to store chemical.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The lowest cost and most efficient one is hydrogen.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it is easier to use synthetic methane with existing infrastructure and appliances, as it is very similar to natural gas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2024, there have been a number of demonstration plants where hydrogen is burned in gas turbines, either co-firing with natural gas, or on its own.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Similarly, a number of coal plants have demonstrated it is possible to co-fire ammonia when burning coal.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In 2022, there was also a small pilot to burn pure ammonia in a gas turbine.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] A portion of existing gas turbines are capable of co-firing hydrogen, which means there is, as a lower estimate, 80 GW of capacity ready to burn hydrogen.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be used as a long-term storage medium.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Green hydrogen is produced from the electrolysis of water and converted back into electricity in an internal combustion engine, or a fuel cell, with a round-trip efficiency of roughly 41%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Together with thermal storage, it is expected to be best suited to seasonal energy storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be stored aboveground in tanks or underground in larger quantities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Underground storage is easiest in salt caverns, but only a certain number of places have suitable geology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Storage in porous rocks, for instance in empty gas fields and some aquifers, can store hydrogen at a larger scale, but this type of storage may have some drawbacks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, some of the hydrogen can leak or react to form hydrogen sulfide (H₂S) or methane.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen can be converted into ammonia in a reaction with nitrogen in the Haber-Bosch process.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia, a gas at room temperature, is more expensive to produce than hydrogen.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, it can be stored more cheaply than hydrogen.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Tank storage is usually done at between one and ten times atmospheric pressure and at a temperature of −30 °C (−22 °F), in liquid form.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Ammonia has multiple uses besides being an energy carrier: it is the basis for the production of many chemicals; the most common use is for fertilizer.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It can be used for power generation directly, or converted back to hydrogen first.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternatively, it has potential applications as a fuel in shipping.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It is possible to further convert hydrogen into methane via the Sabatier reaction, a chemical reaction which combines CO2 and H2.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] While the reaction that converts CO from gasified coal into CH4 is mature, the process to form methane out of CO2 is less so.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Efficiencies of around 80% one-way can be achieved, that is, some 20% of the energy in hydrogen is lost in the reaction.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Flywheels store energy in the form of mechanical energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] They are suited to supplying high levels of electricity over minutes and can also be charged rapidly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] They have a long lifetime and can be used in settings with widely varying temperatures.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The technology is mature, but more expensive than batteries and supercapacitors and not used frequently.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, pumped-storage hydroelectricity (PSH) was the largest form of grid energy storage globally, with an installed capacity of 181 GW, surpassing the combined capacity of utility-scale and behind-the-meter battery storage, which totaled approximately 88 GW.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] PSH is particularly effective for managing daily fluctuations in energy demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] During periods of low demand, water is pumped to a higher-elevation reservoir, and during peak demand, the stored water is released to generate electricity through turbines.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The system has an efficiency rate of 75% to 85% and can quickly respond to changes in demand, typically within seconds to minutes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] While traditional PSH systems require specific geographical conditions, alternative designs have been proposed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] These include using deep salt caverns or constructing hollow structures on the seabed, where the ocean serves as the upper reservoir.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] However, PSH construction is often expensive, time-consuming, and can have significant environmental and social impacts on nearby communities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Installing floating solar panels on reservoirs, can increase the efficiency of PSH systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] These panels reduce water evaporation and benefit from cooling by the water surface, which also improves their energy generation efficiency.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams with large reservoirs can also be operated to provide peak generation at times of peak demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Water is stored in the reservoir during periods of low demand and released through the plant when demand is higher.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] While technically no electricity is stored, the net effect is similar to that of pumped storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydroelectric dams typically offer more storage capacity than dedicated pumped-storage systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Upgrades may be needed so that these dams can respond to variable demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, additional investment may be needed in transmission lines, or additional turbines may need to be installed to increase the peak output from the dam.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As well as energy generation, they often play a role in flood defense and protection of ecosystems, recreation, and they supply water for irrigation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means it is not always possible to change their operation much, but even with low flexibility, they may still play an important role in responding to changes in wind and solar production.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative methods that use gravity include storing energy by moving large solid masses upward against gravity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be achieved inside old mine shafts or in specially constructed towers where heavy weights are winched up to store energy and allowed a controlled descent to release it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Compressed air energy storage (CAES) stores electricity by compressing air.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The compressed air is typically stored in large underground caverns.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The expanding air can be used to drive turbines, converting the energy back into electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As air cools when expanding, some heat needs to be added in this stage to prevent freezing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This can be provided by a low-carbon source, or in the case of advanced CAES, by reusing the heat that is released when air is compressed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, there are three advanced CAES projects in operation in China.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typical efficiencies of advanced CAES are between 60% and 80%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Another electricity storage method is to compress and cool air, turning it into liquid air, which can be stored and expanded when needed, turning a turbine to generate electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is called liquid air energy storage (LAES).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The air would be cooled to temperatures of −196 °C (−320.8 °F) to become liquid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with compressed air, heat is needed for the expansion step.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In the case of LAES, low-grade industrial heat can be used for this.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Energy efficiency for LAES lies between 50% and 70%.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] As of 2023, LAES is moving from pre-commercial to commercial.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] An alternative is the compression of CO 2 to store electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity can be directly stored thermally with a Carnot battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] A Carnot battery is a type of energy storage system that stores electricity in heat storage and converts the stored heat back to electricity via thermodynamic cycles (for instance, a turbine).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] While less efficient than pumped hydro or battery storage, this type of system is expected to be cheap and can provide long-duration storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] A pumped-heat electricity storage system is a Carnot battery that uses a reversible heat pump to convert the electricity into heat.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It usually stores the energy in both a hot and cold reservoir.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] To achieve decent efficiencies (>50%), the temperature ratio between the two must reach a factor of 5.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Thermal energy storage is also used in combination with concentrated solar power (CSP).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In CSP, solar energy is first converted into heat, and then either directly converted into electricity or first stored.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy is released when there is little or no sunshine.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This means that CSP can be used as a dispatchable (flexible) form of generation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The energy in a CSP system can for instance be stored in molten salts or in a solid medium such as sand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Finally, heating and cooling systems in buildings can be controlled to store thermal energy in either the building's mass or dedicated thermal storage tanks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This thermal storage can provide load-shifting or even more complex ancillary services by increasing power consumption (charging the storage) during off-peak times and lowering power consumption (discharging the storage) during higher-priced peak times.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The levelized cost of storing electricity (LCOS) is a measure of the lifetime costs of storing electricity per MWh of electricity discharged.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It includes investment costs, but also operational costs and charging costs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] It depends highly on storage type and purpose; as subsecond-scale frequency regulation, minute/hour-scale peaker plants, or day/week-scale season storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For power applications (for instance around ancillary services or black starts), a similar metric is the annuitized capacity cost (ACC), which measures the lifetime costs per kW.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] ACC is lowest when there are few cycles (<300) and when the discharge is less than one hour.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This is because the technology is reimbursed only when it provides spare capacity, not when it is discharged.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The cost of storage is coming down following technology-dependent experience curves, the price drop for each doubling in cumulative capacity (or experience).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Lithium-ion battery prices fall rapidly: the price utilities pay for them falls 19% with each doubling of capacity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Hydrogen production via electrolysis has a similar learning rate, but it is much more uncertain.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Vanadium-flow batteries typically get 14% cheaper for each doubling of capacity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Pumped hydropower has not seen prices fall much with increased experience.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Before 2020, most value for storage was in providing power quality services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Arbitrage is the service with the largest economic potential for storage applications.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] In systems with under 40% of variable renewables, only short-term storage (of less than 4 hours) is needed for integration.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] When the share of variable renewables climbs to 80%, medium-duration storage (between 4 and 16 hours, for instance compressed air) is needed.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Above 90%, large-scale long-duration storage is required.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The economics of long-duration storage is challenging even then, as the costs are high.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Alternative flexibility options, such as demand response, network expansions or flexible generation (geothermal or fossil gas with carbon capture and storage) may be lower-cost.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Like with renewables, storage will "cannibalise" its own income, but even more strongly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] That is, with more storage on the market, there is less of an opportunity to do arbitrage or deliver other services to the grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] How markets are designed impacts revenue potential too.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] The income from arbitrage is quite variable between years, whereas markets that have capacity payments likely show less volatility.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Electricity storage is not 100% efficient, so more electricity needs to be bought than can be sold.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] This implies that if there is only a small variation in price, it may not be economical to charge and discharge.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] For instance, if the storage application is 75% efficient, the price at which the electricity is sold needs to be at least 1.33 higher than the price for which it was bought.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/grid-energy-storage] Typically, electricity prices vary most between day and night, which means that storage up to 8 hours has relatively high potential for profit.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The **smart grid** is an enhancement of the 20th century electrical grid, using two-way communications and distributed so-called intelligent devices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Two-way flows of electricity and information could improve the delivery network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Research is mainly focused on three systems of a smart grid – the infrastructure system, the management system, and the protection system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Electronic power conditioning and control of the production and distribution of electricity are important aspects of the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid represents the full suite of current and proposed responses to the challenges of electricity supply.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Numerous contributions to the overall improvement of energy infrastructure efficiency are anticipated from the deployment of smart grid technology, in particular including demand-side management.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The improved flexibility of the smart grid permits greater penetration of highly variable renewable energy sources such as solar power and wind power, even without the addition of energy storage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids could also monitor/control residential devices that are noncritical during periods of peak power consumption, and return their function during nonpeak hours.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Concerns with smart grid technology mostly focus on smart meters, items enabled by them, and general security issues.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Roll-out of smart grid technology also implies a fundamental re-engineering of the electricity services industry, although typical usage of the term is focused on the technical infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid policy is organized in Europe as Smart Grid European Technology Platform.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Policy in the United States is described in Title 42 of the United States Code.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids are not to be confused with sector coupled smart energy systems, as smart grids primarily refers to the power sector, while smart energy system use an integrated holistic focus which also includes other sectors of the energy system with the intent to create synergies between them.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The first alternating current power grid system was installed in 1886 in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] At that time, the grid was a centralized unidirectional system of electric power transmission, electricity distribution, and demand-driven control.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 20th century, local grids grew over time and were eventually interconnected for economic and reliability reasons.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Power stations were located strategically to be close to fossil fuel reserves (either the mines or wells themselves or else close to rail, road, or port supply lines).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Siting of hydroelectric dams in mountain areas also strongly influenced the structure of the emerging grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Nuclear power plants were sited for the availability of cooling water.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Finally, fossil fuel-fired power stations were initially very polluting and were sited as far as economically possible from population centres once electricity distribution networks permitted it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] By the late 1960s, the electricity grid reached the overwhelming majority of the population of developed countries, with only outlying regional areas remaining 'off-grid'.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Metering of electricity consumption was necessary on a per-user basis in order to allow appropriate billing according to the (highly variable) level of consumption of different users.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Because of limited data collection and processing capability during the period of growth of the grid, fixed-tariff arrangements were commonly put in place, as well as dual-tariff arrangements where night-time power was charged at a lower rate than daytime power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The motivation for dual-tariff arrangements was the lower night-time demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The metering capabilities of the 1960s grid meant technological limitations on the degree to which price signals could be propagated through the system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] From the 1970s to the 1990s, growing demand led to increasing numbers of power stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In some areas, the supply of electricity, especially at peak times, could not keep up with this demand, resulting in poor power quality including blackouts, power cuts, and brownouts.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Increasingly, electricity was depended on for industry, heating, communication, lighting, and entertainment, and consumers demanded ever-higher levels of reliability.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Towards the end of the 20th century, electricity demand patterns were established: domestic heating and air-conditioning led to daily peaks in demand that were met by an array of 'peaking power generators' that would only be turned on for short periods each day.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 21st century, some developing countries like China, India, and Brazil were seen as pioneers of smart grid deployment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Since the early 21st century, opportunities to take advantage of improvements in electronic communication technology to resolve the limitations and costs of the electrical grid have become apparent.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Technological limitations on metering no longer force peak power prices to be averaged out and passed on to all consumers equally.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In parallel, growing concerns over environmental damage from fossil-fired power stations have led to a desire to use large amounts of renewable energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Dominant forms such as wind power and solar power are highly variable, and so the need for more sophisticated control systems became apparent, to facilitate the connection of sources to the otherwise highly controllable grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Power from photovoltaic cells (and to lesser extent wind turbines) has also, significantly, called into question the imperative for large, centralised power stations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The rapidly falling costs point to a major change from the centralised grid topology to one that is highly distributed, with power being both generated *and* consumed right at the limits of the grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Finally, growing concern over terrorist attacks in some countries has led to calls for a more robust energy grid that is less dependent on centralised power stations that were perceived to be potential attack targets.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The first official definition of Smart Grid was provided by the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA-2007), which was approved by the US Congress in January 2007, and signed to law by President George W.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] That definition was used in the European Commission Communication (2011) 202.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A common element to most definitions is the application of digital processing and communications to the power grid, making data flow and information management central to the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Various capabilities result from the deeply integrated use of digital technology with power grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Integration of the new grid information is one of the key issues in the design of smart grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Much of the work that has been going on in electric grid modernization, especially substation and distribution automation, is now included in the general concept of the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technologies emerged from earlier attempts at using electronic control, metering, and monitoring.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the 1980s, automatic meter reading was used for monitoring loads from large customers and evolved into the Advanced Metering Infrastructure of the 1990s, whose meters could store how electricity was used at different times of the day.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart meters add continuous communications so that monitoring can be done in real-time, and can be used as a gateway to demand response-aware devices and "smart sockets" in the home.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Early forms of such demand side management technologies were dynamic demand aware devices that passively sensed the load on the grid by monitoring changes in the power supply frequency.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Devices such as industrial and domestic air conditioners, refrigerators, and heaters adjusted their duty cycle to avoid activation during times the grid was suffering a peak condition.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Beginning in 2000, Italy's Telegestore Project was the first to network large numbers (27 million) of homes using smart meters connected via low bandwidth power line communication.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Some experiments used the term broadband over power lines (BPL), while others used wireless technologies such as mesh networking promoted for more reliable connections to disparate devices in the home as well as supporting metering of other utilities such as gas and water.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Monitoring and synchronization of wide-area networks were revolutionized in the early 1990s when the Bonneville Power Administration expanded its smart grid research with prototype sensors that are capable of very rapid analysis of anomalies in electricity quality over very large geographic areas.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The culmination of this work was the first operational Wide Area Measurement System (WAMS) in 2000.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Other countries are rapidly integrating this technology — China started having a comprehensive national WAMS when the past 5-year economic plan was completed in 2012.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The earliest deployments of smart grids include the Italian system *Telegestore* (2005), the mesh network of Austin, Texas (since 2003), and the smart grid in Boulder, Colorado (2008).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] See § Deployments and attempted deployments below.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid would allow the power industry to observe and control parts of the system at higher resolution in time and space.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] One of the purposes of the smart grid is real time information exchange to make operation as efficient as possible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] It would allow management of the grid on all time scales from high-frequency switching devices on a microsecond scale, to wind and solar output variations on a minute scale, to the future effects of the carbon emissions generated by power production on a decade scale.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Because of the diverse range of factors, there are numerous competing taxonomies and no agreement on a universal definition.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Nevertheless, one possible categorization is given here.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid makes use of technologies such as state estimation, that improve fault detection and allow self-healing of the network without the intervention of technicians.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This will ensure a more reliable supply of electricity and reduce vulnerability to natural disasters or attacks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although multiple routes are touted as a feature of the smart grid, the old grid also featured multiple routes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Initial power lines in the grid were built using a radial model, later connectivity was guaranteed via multiple routes, referred to as a network structure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] However, this created a new problem: if the current flow or related effects across the network exceed the limits of any particular network element, it could fail, and the current would be shunted to other network elements, which eventually may fail also, causing a domino effect.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A technique to prevent this is load shedding by rolling blackout or voltage reduction (brownout).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Classic grids were designed for a one-way flow of electricity, but if a local sub-network generates more power than it is consuming, the reverse flow can raise safety and reliability issues.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid aims to manage these situations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is less redundancy in transmission and distribution lines, and greater utilization of generators, leading to lower power prices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total load connected to the power grid can vary significantly over time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although the total load is the sum of many individual choices of the clients, the overall load is not necessarily stable or slow varying.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] For example, if a popular television program starts, millions of televisions will start to draw current instantly.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Traditionally, to respond to a rapid increase in power consumption, faster than the start-up time of a large generator, some spare generators are put on a dissipative standby mode.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A smart grid may warn all individual television sets, or another larger customer, to reduce the load temporarily (to allow time to start up a larger generator) or continuously (in the case of limited resources).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Using mathematical prediction algorithms it is possible to predict how many standby generators need to be used, to reach a certain failure rate.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In the traditional grid, the failure rate can only be reduced at the cost of more standby generators.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In a smart grid, the load reduction by even a small portion of the clients may eliminate the problem.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] To reduce demand during the high-cost peak usage periods, communications and metering technologies inform smart devices in the home and business when energy demand is high and track how much electricity is used and when it is used.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] It also gives utility companies the ability to reduce consumption by communicating to devices directly in order to prevent system overloads.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Examples would be a utility reducing the usage of a group of electric vehicle charging stations or shifting temperature set points of air conditioners in a city.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] To motivate them to cut back use and perform what is called **peak curtailment** or **peak leveling**, prices of electricity are increased during high demand periods and decreased during low demand periods.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] It is thought that consumers and businesses will tend to consume less during high-demand periods if it is possible for consumers and consumer devices to be aware of the high price premium for using electricity at peak periods.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This could mean making trade-offs such as cycling on/off air conditioners or running dishwashers at 9 pm instead of 5 pm.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] When businesses and consumers see a direct economic benefit of using energy at off-peak times, the theory is that they will include the energy cost of operation into their consumer device and building construction decisions and hence become more energy efficient.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Current network infrastructure is not built to allow for many distributed feed-in points, and typically even if some feed-in is allowed at the local (distribution) level, the transmission-level infrastructure cannot accommodate it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Rapid fluctuations in distributed generation, such as due to cloudy or gusty weather, present significant challenges to power engineers who need to ensure stable power levels through varying the output of the more controllable generators such as gas turbines and hydroelectric generators.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grid technology is a necessary condition for very large amounts of renewable electricity on the grid for this reason.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] There is also support for vehicle-to-grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The smart grid allows for systematic communication between suppliers (their energy price) and consumers (their willingness-to-pay), and permits both the suppliers and the consumers to be more flexible and sophisticated in their operational strategies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Only the critical loads will need to pay the peak energy prices, and consumers will be able to be more strategic in when they use energy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Generators with greater flexibility will be able to sell energy strategically for maximum profit, whereas inflexible generators such as base-load steam turbines and wind turbines will receive a varying tariff based on the level of demand and the status of the other generators currently operating.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The overall effect is a signal that awards energy efficiency, and energy consumption that is sensitive to the time-varying limitations of the supply.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] At the domestic level, appliances with a degree of energy storage or thermal mass (such as refrigerators, heat banks, and heat pumps) will be well placed to 'play' the market and seek to minimise energy cost by adapting demand to the lower-cost energy support periods.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This is an extension of the dual-tariff energy pricing mentioned above.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Demand response support allows generators and loads to interact in an automated fashion in real-time, coordinating demand to flatten spikes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Eliminating the fraction of demand that occurs in these spikes eliminates the cost of adding reserve generators, cuts wear and tear and extends the life of equipment, and allows users to cut their energy bills by telling low priority devices to use energy only when it is cheapest.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Currently, power grid systems have varying degrees of communication within control systems for their high-value assets, such as in generating plants, transmission lines, substations, and major energy users.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In general, information flows one way, from the users and the loads they control back to the utilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The utilities attempt to meet the demand and succeed or fail to varying degrees (brownouts, rolling blackout, uncontrolled blackout).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total amount of power demanded by the users can have a very wide probability distribution which requires spare generating plants in standby mode to respond to the rapidly changing power usage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This one-way flow of information is expensive; the last 10% of generating capacity may be required as little as 1% of the time, and brownouts and outages can be costly to consumers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Demand response can be provided by commercial, residential loads, and industrial loads.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] For example, Alcoa's Warrick Operation is participating in MISO as a qualified Demand Response Resource, and the Trimet Aluminium uses its smelter as a short-term mega-battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Latency of the data flow is a major concern, with some early smart meter architectures allowing actually as long as 24 hours delay in receiving the data, preventing any possible reaction by either supplying or demanding devices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The bulk of smart grid technologies are already used in other applications such as manufacturing and telecommunications and are being adapted for use in grid operations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Many different concepts have been used to model intelligent power grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] They are generally studied within the framework of complex systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In a recent brainstorming session, the power grid was considered within the context of optimal control, ecology, human cognition, glassy dynamics, information theory, microphysics of clouds, and many others.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Here is a selection of the types of analyses that have appeared in recent years.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Evans in their study introduced the concept of a substation based smart protection and hybrid Inspection Unit.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The power grid has been mapped onto variations of the Kuramoto model, a well-studied framework for synchronization of nonlinear oscillators.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The model describes how the electrical system keeps the power balance, to maintain phase synchronization (also known as phase locking).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Strictly speaking, the model is most used for an ordinary electrical grid, to determine, for instance, the role of branch insertions or of parameters dispersion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Non-uniform oscillators also help to model different technologies, different types of power generators, patterns of consumption, and so on.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The model has also been used to describe the synchronization patterns in the blinking of fireflies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Network Simulators are used to simulate/emulate network communication effects.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This typically involves setting up a lab with the smart grid devices, applications etc. with the virtual network being provided by the network simulator.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Neural networks have been considered for power grid management as well.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Electric power systems can be classified in multiple different ways: non-linear, dynamic, discrete, or random.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) attempt to solve the most difficult of these problems, the non-linear problems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] One application of ANNs is in demand forecasting.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In order for grids to operate economically and reliably, demand forecasting is essential, because it is used to predict the amount of power that will be consumed by the load.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] This is dependent on weather conditions, type of day, random events, incidents, etc.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] For non-linear loads though, the load profile isn't smooth and as predictable, resulting in higher uncertainty and less accuracy using the traditional Artificial Intelligence models.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] An example of the last case would be given the type of day, whether its weekday or weekend, that wouldn't have much of an effect on Hospital grids, but it'd be a big factor in resident housing grids' load profile.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] As wind power continues to gain popularity, it becomes a necessary ingredient in realistic power grid studies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Off-line storage, wind variability, supply, demand, pricing, and other factors can be modelled as a mathematical game.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Here the goal is to develop a winning strategy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Markov processes have been used to model and study this type of system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] In 2009, the US smart grid industry was valued at about $21.4 billion – by 2014, it will exceed at least $42.8 billion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Given the success of the smart grids in the U.S., the world market is expected to grow at a faster rate, surging from $69.3 billion in 2009 to $171.4 billion by 2014.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] With the segments set to benefit the most will be smart metering hardware sellers and makers of software used to transmit and organize the massive amount of data collected by meters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2011 study from the Electric Power Research Institute concludes that investment in a U.S. smart grid will cost up to $476 billion over 20 years but will provide up to $2 trillion in customer benefits over that time.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2019 study from International Energy Agency estimates that the current (depreciated) value of the US electric grid is more than US$1 trillion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The total cost of replacing it with a smart grid is estimated to be more than US$4 trillion.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] If smart grids are deployed fully across the US, the country expects to save US$130 billion annually.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] As customers can choose their electricity suppliers, depending on their different tariff methods, the focus of transportation costs will be increased.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Reduction of maintenance and replacements costs will stimulate more advanced control.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A 2003 United States Department of Energy study calculated that internal modernization of US grids with smart grid capabilities would save between 46 and 117 billion dollars over the next 20 years if implemented within a few years of the study.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] As well as these industrial modernization benefits, smart grid features could expand energy efficiency beyond the grid into the home by coordinating low priority home devices such as water heaters so that their use of power takes advantage of the most desirable energy sources.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Smart grids can also coordinate the production of power from large numbers of small power producers such as owners of rooftop solar panels — an arrangement that would otherwise prove problematic for power systems operators at local utilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] One important question is whether consumers will act in response to market signals.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Another concern is that the cost of telecommunications to fully support smart grids may be prohibitive.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] A less expensive communication mechanism is proposed using a form of "dynamic demand management" where devices shave peaks by shifting their loads in reaction to grid frequency.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Grid frequency could be used to communicate load information without the need of an additional telecommunication network, but it would not support economic bargaining or quantification of contributions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] Although there are specific and proven smart grid technologies in use, *smart grid* is an aggregate term for a set of related technologies on which a specification is generally agreed, rather than a name for a specific technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p01] The increased efficiency and reliability of the smart grid is expected to save consumers money and help reduce CO2 emissions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most opposition and concerns have centered on smart meters and the items (such as remote control, remote disconnect, and variable rate pricing) enabled by them.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Where opposition to smart meters is encountered, they are often marketed as "smart grid" which connects smart grid to smart meters in the eyes of opponents.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] While modernization of electrical grids into smart grids allows for optimization of everyday processes, a smart grid, being online, can be vulnerable to cyberattacks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Transformers which increase the voltage of electricity created at power plants for long-distance travel, transmission lines themselves, and distribution lines which deliver the electricity to its consumers are particularly susceptible.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These systems rely on sensors which gather information from the field and then deliver it to control centers, where algorithms automate analysis and decision-making processes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These decisions are sent back to the field, where existing equipment execute them.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hackers have the potential to disrupt these automated control systems, severing the channels which allow generated electricity to be utilized.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This is called a denial of service or DoS attack.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] They can also launch integrity attacks which corrupt information being transmitted along the system as well as desynchronization attacks which affect when such information is delivered to the appropriate location.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, intruders can gain access via renewable energy generation systems and smart meters connected to the grid, taking advantage of more specialized weaknesses or ones whose security has not been prioritized.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Because a smart grid has a large number of access points, like smart meters, defending all of its weak points can prove difficult.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs) have evolved to target smart grids by reprogramming Programmable Logic Controllers (PLCs) to display false 'normal' operating conditions to operators while causing physical damage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] To counter these vulnerabilities, experts recommend shifting from traditional network segmentation to 'micro-segmentation' and adopting 'zero-trust' models that require verification at every layer of the infrastructure.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] There is also concern on the security of the infrastructure, primarily that involving communications technology.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Concerns chiefly center around the communications technology at the heart of the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Designed to allow real-time contact between utilities and meters in customers' homes and businesses, there is a risk that these capabilities could be exploited for criminal or even terrorist actions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the key capabilities of this connectivity is the ability to remotely switch off power supplies, enabling utilities to quickly and easily cease or modify supplies to customers who default on payment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This is undoubtedly a massive boon for energy providers, but also raises some significant security issues.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Cybercriminals have infiltrated the U.S. electric grid before on numerous occasions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Aside from computer infiltration, there are also concerns that computer malware like Stuxnet, which targeted SCADA systems which are widely used in industry, could be used to attack a smart grid network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft is a concern in the U.S. where the smart meters being deployed use RF technology to communicate with the electricity transmission network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] People with knowledge of electronics can devise interference devices to cause the smart meter to report lower than actual usage.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Similarly, the same technology can be employed to make it appear that the energy the consumer is using is being used by another customer, increasing their bill.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The damage from a well-executed, sizable cyberattack could be extensive and long-lasting.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] One incapacitated substation could take from nine days to over a year to repair, depending on the nature of the attack.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It can also cause an hours-long outage in a small radius.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It could have an immediate effect on transportation infrastructure, as traffic lights and other routing mechanisms as well as ventilation equipment for underground roadways is reliant on electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, infrastructure which relies on the electric grid, including wastewater treatment facilities, the information technology sector, and communications systems could be impacted.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The December 2015 Ukraine power grid cyberattack, the first recorded of its kind, disrupted services to nearly a quarter of a million people by bringing substations offline.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Council on Foreign Relations has noted that states are most likely to be the perpetrators of such an attack as they have access to the resources to carry one out despite the high level of difficulty of doing so.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Cyber intrusions can be used as portions of a larger offensive, military or otherwise.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some security experts warn that this type of event is easily scalable to grids elsewhere.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Insurance company Lloyd's of London has already modeled the outcome of a cyberattack on the Eastern Interconnection, which has the potential to impact 15 states, put 93 million people in the dark, and cost the country's economy anywhere from $243 billion to $1 trillion in various damages.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] House of Representatives Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings, and Emergency Management, the electric grid has already seen a sizable number of cyber intrusions, with two in every five aiming to incapacitate it.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Department of Energy has prioritized research and development to decrease the electric grid's vulnerability to cyberattacks, citing them as an "imminent danger" in its 2017 Quadrennial Energy Review.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy has also identified both attack resistance and self-healing as major keys to ensuring that today's smart grid is future-proof.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] While there are regulations already in place, namely the Critical Infrastructure Protection Standards introduced by the North America Electric Reliability Council, a significant number of them are suggestions rather than mandates.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most electricity generation, transmission, and distribution facilities and equipment are owned by private stakeholders, further complicating the task of assessing adherence to such standards.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, even if utilities want to fully comply, they may find that it is too expensive to do so.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some experts argue that the first step to increasing the cyber defenses of the smart electric grid is completing a comprehensive risk analysis of existing infrastructure, including research of software, hardware, and communication processes.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Additionally, as intrusions themselves can provide valuable information, it could be useful to analyze system logs and other records of their nature and timing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Common weaknesses already identified using such methods by the Department of Homeland Security include poor code quality, improper authentication, and weak firewall rules.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Once this step is completed, some suggest that it makes sense to then complete an analysis of the potential consequences of the aforementioned failures or shortcomings.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This includes both immediate consequences as well as second- and third-order cascading effects on parallel systems.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Finally, risk mitigation solutions, which may include simple remediation of infrastructure inadequacies or novel strategies, can be deployed to address the situation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some such measures include recoding of control system algorithms to make them more able to resist and recover from cyberattacks or preventive techniques that allow more efficient detection of unusual or unauthorized changes to data.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Strategies to account for human error which can compromise systems include educating those who work in the field to be wary of strange USB drives, which can introduce malware if inserted, even if just to check their contents.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Other solutions include utilizing transmission substations, constrained SCADA networks, policy based data sharing, and attestation for constrained smart meters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Transmission substations utilize one-time signature authentication technologies and one-way hash chain constructs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These constraints have since been remedied with the creation of a fast-signing and verification technology and buffering-free data processing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] A similar solution has been constructed for constrained SCADA networks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This involves applying a Hash-Based Message Authentication Code to byte streams, converting the random-error detection available on legacy systems to a mechanism that guarantees data authenticity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Policy-based data sharing utilizes GPS-clock-synchronized-fine-grain power grid measurements to provide increased grid stability and reliability.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It does this through synchro-phasor requirements that are gathered by PMUs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Attestation for constrained smart meters faces a slightly different challenge, however.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the biggest issues with attestation for constrained smart meters is that in order to prevent energy theft, and similar attacks, cyber security providers have to make sure that the devices' software is authentic.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] To combat this problem, an architecture for constrained smart networks has been created and implemented at a low level in the embedded system.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The protection system of a smart grid provides grid reliability analysis, failure protection, and security and privacy protection services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] While the additional communication infrastructure of a smart grid provides additional protective and security mechanisms, it also presents a risk of external attack and internal failures.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Before a utility installs an advanced metering system, or any type of smart system, it must make a business case for the investment.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some components, like the power system stabilizers (PSS) installed on generators are very expensive, require complex integration in the grid's control system, are needed only during emergencies, and are only effective if other suppliers on the network have them.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Without any incentive to install them, power suppliers don't.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Most utilities find it difficult to justify installing a communications infrastructure for a single application (e.g. meter reading).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Because of this, a utility must typically identify several applications that will use the same communications infrastructure – for example, reading a meter, monitoring power quality, remote connection and disconnection of customers, enabling demand response, etc.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Ideally, the communications infrastructure will not only support near-term applications, but unanticipated applications that will arise in the future.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Regulatory or legislative actions can also drive utilities to implement pieces of a smart grid puzzle.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Each utility has a unique set of business, regulatory, and legislative drivers that guide its investments.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This means that each utility will take a different path to creating their smart grid and that different utilities will create smart grids at different adoption rates.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some features of smart grids draw opposition from industries that currently are, or hope to provide similar services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] An example is competition with cable and DSL Internet providers from broadband over powerline internet access.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Providers of SCADA control systems for grids have intentionally designed proprietary hardware, protocols and software so that they cannot inter-operate with other systems in order to tie its customers to the vendor.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The incorporation of digital communications and computer infrastructure with the grid's existing physical infrastructure poses challenges and inherent vulnerabilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] According to *IEEE Security & Privacy*, the smart grid will require that people develop and use large computer and communication infrastructure that supports a greater degree of situational awareness and that allows for more specific command and control operations.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This process is necessary to support major systems such as demand-response wide-area measurement and control, storage and transportation of electricity, and the automation of electric distribution.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Various "smart grid" systems have dual functions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This includes Advanced Metering Infrastructure systems which, when used with various software can be used to detect power theft and by process of elimination, detect where equipment failures have taken place.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These are in addition to their primary functions of eliminating the need for human meter reading and measuring the time-of-use of electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The worldwide power loss including theft is estimated at two-hundred billion dollars annually.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Electricity theft also represents a major challenge when providing reliable electrical service in developing countries.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The earliest, and one of the largest, example of a smart grid is the Italian system installed by Enel S.p.A. of Italy.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Completed in 2005, the Telegestore project was highly unusual in the utility world because the company designed and manufactured their own meters, acted as their own system integrator, and developed their own system software.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Telegestore project is widely regarded as the first commercial scale use of smart grid technology to the home, and delivers annual savings of 500 million euro at a project cost of 2.1 billion euro.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the largest deployment programs in the world to-date is the U.S.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Dept. of Energy's Smart Grid Program funded by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This program required matching funding from individual utilities.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] A total of over $9 billion in Public/Private funds were invested as part of this program.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This program consisted of Investment Grants (matching), Demonstration Projects, Consumer Acceptance Studies, and Workforce Education Programs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Reports from all individual utility programs as well as overall impact reports will be completed by the second quarter of 2015.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the U.S., the Energy Policy Act of 2005 and Title XIII of the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 are providing funding to encourage smart grid development.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The objective is to enable utilities to better predict their needs, and in some cases involve consumers in a time-of-use tariff.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Funds have also been allocated to develop more robust energy control technologies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the US, the city of Austin, Texas, has been working on building its smart grid since 2003, when its utility first replaced 1/3 of its manual meters with smart meters that communicate via a wireless mesh network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It currently manages 200,000 devices real-time (smart meters, smart thermostats, and sensors across its service area), and expects to be supporting 500,000 devices real-time in 2009 servicing 1 million consumers and 43,000 businesses.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Boulder, Colorado, completed the first phase of its smart grid project in August 2008.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Both systems use the smart meter as a gateway to the home automation network (HAN) that controls smart sockets and devices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Some HAN designers favor decoupling control functions from the meter, out of concern of future mismatches with new standards and technologies available from the fast moving business segment of home electronic devices.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hydro One, in Ontario, Canada is in the midst of a large-scale Smart Grid initiative, deploying a standards-compliant communications infrastructure from Trilliant.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] By the end of 2010, the system will serve 1.3 million customers in the province of Ontario.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The initiative won the "Best AMR Initiative in North America" award from the Utility Planning Network.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Île d'Yeu began a 2-year pilot program in Spring of 2020.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Twenty-three houses in the Ker Pissot neighborhood and surrounding areas were interconnected with a microgrid that was automated as a smart grid with software from Engie.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Sixty-four solar panels with a peak capacity of 23.7 kW were installed on five houses and a battery with a storage capacity of 15 kWh was installed on one house.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Six houses store excess solar energy in their hot water heaters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] A dynamic system apportions the energy provided by the solar panels and stored in the battery and hot water heaters to the system of 23 houses.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid software dynamically updates energy supply and demand in 5 minute intervals, deciding whether to pull energy from the battery or from the panels and when to store it in the hot water heaters.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This pilot program was the first such project in France.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The City of Mannheim in Germany is using realtime Broadband Powerline (BPL) communications in its Model City Mannheim "MoMa" project.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Sydney also in Australia, in partnership with the Australian Government implemented the Smart Grid, Smart City program.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It will be possible to control and manage the state of the entire electricity distribution grid at any given instant, allowing suppliers and energy services companies to use this technological platform to offer consumers information and added-value energy products and services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This project to install an intelligent energy grid places Portugal and EDP at the cutting edge of technological innovation and service provision in Europe.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the so-called *E-Energy* projects several German utilities are creating first nucleolus in six independent model regions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] A technology competition identified this model regions to carry out research and development activities with the main objective to create an "Internet of Energy".
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] One of the first attempted deployments of "smart grid" technologies in the United States was rejected in 2009 by electricity regulators in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, a US state.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This plan was rejected by regulators as it "eroded important protections for low-income customers against shutoffs".
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] According to the Boston Globe, the plan "unfairly targeted low-income customers and circumvented Massachusetts laws meant to help struggling consumers keep the lights on".
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In the Netherlands a large-scale project (>5000 connections, >20 partners) was initiated to demonstrate integrated smart grids technologies, services and business cases.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] EPB in Chattanooga, TN is a municipally owned electric utility that started construction of a smart grid in 2008, receiving a $111,567,606 grant from the US DOE in 2009 to expedite construction and implementation (for a total budget of $232,219,350).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Deployment of power-line interrupters (1170 units) was completed in April 2012, and deployment of smart meters (172,079 units) was completed in 2013.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid's backbone fiber-optic system was also used to provide the first gigabit-speed internet connection to residential customers in the US through the Fiber to the Home initiative, and now speeds of up to 10 gigabits per second are available to residents.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid is estimated to have reduced power outages by an average of 60%, saving the city about 60 million dollars annually.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It has also reduced the need for "truck rolls" to scout and troubleshoot faults, resulting in an estimated reduction of 630,000 truck driving miles, and 4.7 million pounds of carbon emissions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In January 2016, EPB became the first major power distribution system to earn Performance Excellence in Electricity Renewal (PEER) certification.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Certain deployments utilize the OpenADR standard for load shedding and demand reduction during higher demand periods.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The smart grid market in China is estimated to be $22.3 billion with a projected growth to $61.4 billion by 2015.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Honeywell is developing a demand response pilot and feasibility study for China with the State Grid Corp. of China using the OpenADR demand response standard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The State Grid Corp., the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and General Electric intend to work together to develop standards for China's smart grid rollout.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In 2009, the US Department of Energy awarded an $11 million grant to Southern California Edison and Honeywell for a demand response program that automatically turns down energy use during peak hours for participating industrial customers.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The Department of Energy awarded an $11.4 million grant to Honeywell to implement the program using the OpenADR standard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] (HECO) is implementing a two-year pilot project to test the ability of an ADR program to respond to the intermittence of wind power.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Hawaii has a goal to obtain 70 percent of its power from renewable sources by 2030.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] HECO will give customers incentives for reducing power consumption within 10 minutes of a notice.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Part of the IEEE Smart Grid Initiative, IEEE 2030.2 represents an extension of the work aimed at utility storage systems for transmission and distribution networks.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE P2030 group expects to deliver early 2011 an overarching set of guidelines on smart grid interfaces.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The new guidelines will cover areas including batteries and supercapacitors as well as flywheels.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The group has also spun out a 2030.1 effort drafting guidelines for integrating electric vehicles into the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] IEC TC 57 has created a family of international standards that can be used as part of the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These standards include IEC 61850 which is an architecture for substation automation, and IEC 61970/61968 – the Common Information Model (CIM).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The CIM provides for common semantics to be used for turning data into information.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] OpenADR is an open-source smart grid communications standard used for demand response applications.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] It is typically used to send information and signals to cause electrical power-using devices to be turned off during periods of higher demand.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has created a specification that supports distribution functionality of the smart grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak has a robust set of integration definitions that supports nearly all of the software interfaces necessary for a distribution utility or for the distribution portion of a vertically integrated utility.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] MultiSpeak integration is defined using extensible markup language (XML) and web services.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The IEEE has created a standard to support synchrophasors – C37.118.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The UCA International User Group discusses and supports real world experience of the standards used in smart grids.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] A utility task group within LonMark International deals with smart grid related issues.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] There is a growing trend towards the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for smart meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] IEEE P2030 is an IEEE project developing a "Draft Guide for Smart Grid Interoperability of Energy Technology and Information Technology Operation with the Electric Power System (EPS), and End-Use Applications and Loads".
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] NIST has included ITU-T G.hn as one of the "Standards Identified for Implementation" for the Smart Grid "for which it believed there was strong stakeholder consensus".
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] G.hn is standard for high-speed communications over power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] OASIS EnergyInterop' – An OASIS technical committee developing XML standards for energy interoperation.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Its starting point is the California OpenADR standard.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] Under the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA), NIST is charged with overseeing the identification and selection of hundreds of standards that will be required to implement the Smart Grid in the U.S.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] These standards will be referred by NIST to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] This work has begun, and the first standards have already been selected for inclusion in NIST's Smart Grid catalog.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] However, some commentators have suggested that the benefits that could be realized from Smart Grid standardization could be threatened by a growing number of patents that cover Smart Grid architecture and technologies.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] If patents that cover standardized Smart Grid elements are not revealed until technology is broadly distributed throughout the network ("locked-in"), significant disruption could occur when patent holders seek to collect unanticipated rents from large segments of the market.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] In November 2017 the non-profit GridWise Alliance along with Clean Edge Inc., a clean energy group, released rankings for all 50 states in their efforts to modernize the electric grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/smart-grid-p02] The other top states were Illinois, Texas, Maryland, Oregon, Arizona, the District of Columbia, New York, Nevada and Delaware.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Plug-in electric vehicles include battery electric vehicles (BEVs) and plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEVs).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] They share the ability to store electricity in their on-board battery modules, which are typically used to propel the vehicle's electric engine.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] V2G allows some of this energy storage to be sent to the grid, turning the vehicle into a small-scale grid battery that is eligible for claiming feed-in tariffs.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] A 2015 report found that vehicle owners could receive significant payments by charging their EVs at off-peak times when grid electricity is cheaper, storing it in their car battery, and selling it back to the grid at peak times when electricity prices are higher due to congestion pricing.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Rechargeable batteries have a finite number of charge cycles, as well as a limited shelf-life, so V2G can reduce battery longevity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Battery capacity is a complex function of battery chemistry, charge/discharge rates, temperature, state of charge and age, but is improving as technology improves.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Most studies of the effects of V2G on battery life show that slower V2G discharge rates lessen degradation, while one study suggested that using vehicles for grid storage could improve longevity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Some hydrogen fuel cell vehicles (HFCVs) are also equipped with V2G functions.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] HFCVs with fuel tanks containing 5.6 kg (12 lb) of hydrogen fuel can deliver more than 90 kWh of electricity.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Vehicle batteries may hold 100 kWh or more.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Uni-directional V2G (UV2G) charging is technically simpler than delivering power from an EV battery, which many PIEVs are not equipped to do.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] As of 2024, most EVs require a separate inverter than the one used to power the propulsion motors in order to output AC power from the battery.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] UV2G can be extended by throttling other activities such as air heating and cooling.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] V2G began as vehicle-to-vehicle (V2V) charging, as introduced by California company AC Propulsion in the early 1990s.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Their two-seater Tzero car featured two-way charging.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] V2G allows charging and discharging between vehicle and grid.
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] V2G vehicles can provide power to help balance grid loads by "valley filling" (charging at night when demand is low) and "peak shaving" (sending power to the grid when demand is high; see duck curve).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Peak load leveling supports regulation services (keeping voltage and frequency stable) and provides spinning reserves (to meet sudden demands for power).
[src:vehicle-to-grid/vehicle-to-grid] Coupling these services with "smart meters" enables V2G.
